const ALL_QUESTIONS = [
  {id:1,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What is formal verification and how does it differ from simulation?",a:"Formal verification mathematically proves or disproves correctness for ALL possible inputs and states. Simulation checks a finite set of test vectors. FV is exhaustive; simulation can miss corner cases even with millions of cycles."},
  {id:2,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What does FPV stand for and what is its primary use case?",a:"Formal Property Verification. Proves or finds counterexamples for user-written assertions (SVA or PSL) on RTL, without requiring a testbench or stimulus."},
  {id:3,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What are the three main outcomes of a formal property check?",a:"Proven (holds for all reachable states), Falsified (counterexample found), or Inconclusive/Bounded (holds up to depth N, not proven beyond). Some tools also report Vacuous."},
  {id:4,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What is a counterexample (CEX) in formal verification?",a:"A specific sequence of input stimuli and state transitions that leads to an assertion violation. The tool generates a waveform you can load in a simulator to debug. It is the most useful output from FV."},
  {id:5,diff:"Beginner",cat:"SVA",q:"What is an SVA immediate assertion vs. a concurrent assertion?",a:"Immediate: evaluated like a procedural statement at the point it is reached in simulation — no clock edge involved. Concurrent: evaluated over time relative to a clock, can express multi-cycle behaviour using sequence operators."},
  {id:6,diff:"Beginner",cat:"SVA",q:"What is the difference between assume, assert, and cover in SVA?",a:"Assert: tool proves property holds; violations produce a CEX. Assume: constrains input space — treated as axiom, not proven. Cover: tool proves the sequence is reachable; used for reachability analysis and environment sanity-checks."},
  {id:7,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What is a vacuous pass and why is it dangerous?",a:"Occurs when the antecedent of an implication never triggers, so the property is trivially true. The consequent is never checked. Always pair asserts with cover properties on the trigger condition to confirm it actually fires."},
  {id:8,diff:"Beginner",cat:"SVA",q:"Explain |-> vs |=> in SVA with an example.",a:"|-> (overlapping): if antecedent matches at cycle N, consequent is evaluated starting at cycle N (same cycle).\n|=> (non-overlapping): consequent is evaluated starting at cycle N+1.\nExample: req |-> ack means ack must be high the same cycle req fires. req |=> ack means ack must be high the following cycle."},
  {id:9,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What is state space explosion and why does it matter in FV?",a:"The number of reachable states grows exponentially with the number of state bits. Model checkers use symbolic techniques (BDD, SAT, BMC) to handle this implicitly, but complex designs still time out or run out of memory."},
  {id:10,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Algorithms",q:"What is Bounded Model Checking (BMC)?",a:"Unrolls the design transition relation for k clock cycles and encodes reachability as a SAT problem. Finds bugs within depth k but cannot prove a property holds beyond that bound. Good for quick bug-hunting; not a complete proof alone."},
  {id:11,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Algorithms",q:"What is k-induction and when is it used?",a:"Extends BMC to a full proof. Base case: property holds for cycles 0..k. Inductive step: assuming property holds for any k consecutive cycles, prove it holds for cycle k+1. If both pass, the property is proven for all depths."},
  {id:12,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What does 'proof depth' mean in JasperGold?",a:"The number of clock cycles the BMC engine has explored without finding a CEX. A bounded result (CEX-free up to depth N) is not a proof — deeper bugs are not ruled out. A full proof from PDR/IC3 or k-induction is depth-independent."},
  {id:13,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What is the Cone of Influence (COI) in formal verification?",a:"The set of signals that transitively affect the outputs referenced in a given property. FV tools compute COI to prune irrelevant logic and reduce the effective state space. Smaller COI = faster runtimes and more tractable proofs."},
  {id:14,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What is a safety property vs. a liveness property?",a:"Safety: something bad never happens (no overflow, no illegal state). Liveness: something good eventually happens (request is eventually granted). Safety is checked with standard model checking; liveness requires fairness constraints and is significantly harder."},
  {id:15,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Methodology",q:"What is the purpose of assume constraints in FPV?",a:"Prune illegal or impossible input combinations that violate design assumptions. Without them, the solver explores impossible stimulus and generates spurious counterexamples. Assumptions narrow the search to only valid environmental behaviours."},
  {id:16,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Methodology",q:"What is a spurious counterexample?",a:"A CEX produced from input stimulus that can never occur in the real system — caused by missing or incorrect assume constraints. Must be triaged: either add the missing constraint, or confirm the design actually has a bug."},
  {id:17,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What is the difference between FPV and Connectivity Checking (CC)?",a:"FPV proves functional SVA properties written by the engineer. Connectivity Checking verifies structural wiring — no disconnects, shorts, or incorrect connections — typically against a golden netlist. CC requires no user-written assertions."},
  {id:18,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Methodology",q:"Why is a reset constraint essential in an FPV environment?",a:"Forces the design into a valid, known initial state before verification begins. Without it, the solver may start from unreachable X/unknown states, generating spurious CEX and invalidating any proof results."},
  {id:19,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What does 'over-approximation' mean in formal verification?",a:"The abstract model allows more behaviours than the real design — it is a superset. This can cause spurious CEX (false positives). The dual, under-approximation, restricts behaviours and may miss real bugs. Both must be managed in abstraction strategies."},
  {id:20,diff:"Beginner",cat:"SVA",q:"What is the role of cover properties in an FPV environment?",a:"Verify reachability of specific sequences or states. Critical use: sanity-checking assume constraints. If a cover that should be reachable fails, constraints are over-constraining. Also used to demonstrate that key functional scenarios are exercisable."},
  {id:21,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What is blackboxing vs. greyboxing in FV?",a:"Blackboxing replaces a module with completely unconstrained free-variable outputs — maximum abstraction, can cause over-approximation. Greyboxing replaces it with a simplified abstract model capturing only the behaviour relevant to the property being proven."},
  {id:22,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Methodology",q:"What is elaboration in the FV flow?",a:"Resolving parameters, instantiating modules, binding interfaces, and building the internal design hierarchy from RTL. Must succeed without errors before any analysis or proof can begin."},
  {id:23,diff:"Beginner",cat:"RTL",q:"Why are unintended latches in always_comb blocks a problem in FV?",a:"They introduce extra state elements (level-sensitive storage) that increase the state space complexity, can hold stale values masking bugs, and indicate an RTL coding error. FV tools flag them as linting violations."},
  {id:24,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What is a free variable in formal verification?",a:"An unconstrained symbolic value that represents all possible values simultaneously. Undriven input ports become free variables automatically. Used to model unknown inputs or abstract away data content (data path abstraction)."},
  {id:25,diff:"Beginner",cat:"Methodology",q:"What does an 'Inconclusive' result mean and is it a sign-off result?",a:"No CEX was found within the explored depth, but a full proof was not completed. It is NOT a sign-off result. Document the bounded depth and treat it as a partial result — a bug may still exist beyond the explored horizon."},
  {id:26,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Methodology",q:"How do you handle a design too large for full FPV? Name at least four strategies.",a:"1) Blackbox/abstract non-critical submodules to reduce state.\n2) Data path abstraction — replace wide data buses with symbolic free variables.\n3) Case-splitting — partition state space into mutually exclusive cases.\n4) Assume-constrain irrelevant or already-verified inputs.\n5) Compositional/assume-guarantee decomposition.\n6) Reduce bus widths parametrically.\n7) Use bounded proofs as a first pass for bug-hunting."},
  {id:27,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"SVA",q:"Explain $past, $rose, $fell, and $stable in SVA.",a:"$past(sig, N): value of sig N clock cycles ago (defaults to 1).\n$rose(sig): evaluates true when sig transitions 0→1 at this clock edge.\n$fell(sig): evaluates true when sig transitions 1→0 at this clock edge.\n$stable(sig): evaluates true when sig holds the same value as the previous clock edge.\nAll are sampled at the active clock edge of the concurrent property."},
  {id:28,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Protocols",q:"How do you verify a FIFO using FPV? List the key properties.",a:"Full flag: asserted iff count == depth. Empty flag: asserted iff count == 0. No push when full (or overflow protection assert). No pop when empty (or underflow protection assert). Write pointer never overtakes read pointer beyond depth. Data integrity: data pushed is eventually popped in the correct order. Count accurately tracks push/pop operations each cycle."},
  {id:29,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Algorithms",q:"What is induction failure in k-induction and how do you fix it?",a:"The inductive step cannot be proven because the inductive hypothesis is too weak — it allows unreachable states that satisfy the hypothesis but violate the conclusion.\nFixes:\n1) Add invariant strengthening lemmas (auxiliary assertions) that prune the unreachable states.\n2) Increase k so the hypothesis covers more history.\n3) Use IC3/PDR which handles this automatically by constructing an inductive invariant."},
  {id:30,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Algorithms",q:"What is IC3/PDR and how does it differ from BMC?",a:"IC3 (Incremental Construction of Inductive Clauses) / PDR (Property Directed Reachability) builds a sequence of over-approximate reachable state sets (frames) in the original state space without time-unrolling. Unlike BMC, it is not bounded by unrolling depth and naturally discovers inductive invariants. Generally more scalable for safety properties."},
  {id:31,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Protocols",q:"What are the key SVA assertions for a credit-based flow control interface?",a:"1) No underflow: assert property (credit_count == 0 |-> !consume); — do NOT use credit_count >= 0, which is vacuously true for unsigned types.\n2) No overflow: assert property (credit_count == MAX |-> !credit_return);\n3) Transmit only when credits available: assert property (tx_valid |-> credit_count > 0);\n4) Credits never exceed max: assert property (credit_count <= MAX);\n5) Credit returned on completion: cover that credit_count increases after a transaction completes.\n6) Credit count tracks outstanding transactions accurately (via ghost counter comparison)."},
  {id:32,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"SVA",q:"What is the difference between `disable iff` and an assume on the same condition?",a:"`disable iff (rst)` suspends evaluation of a concurrent assertion during the condition without modifying the formal state space — it is a local property-level exception.\nAn assume on the same signal globally constrains input exploration and changes which states the solver considers reachable.\nThey serve fundamentally different semantic purposes — use disable iff for reset exclusion, assume for environment constraints."},
  {id:33,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"SVA",q:"Write a stability property for a signal that must not deassert once set.",a:"The canonical sticky-bit property — once set, never clears until reset:\n\nassert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)\n  set_flag |=> set_flag);\n\nThis says: whenever set_flag is high, it must also be high the following cycle. Combined with reset exclusion via disable iff, this correctly models a sticky bit.\n\nCommon mistake: using $rose(set_flag) |-> ##[0:$] set_flag — the unbounded ##[0:$] means 'holds for zero or more cycles eventually' which does not prevent a deassert; it just requires set_flag to be high at some point after the rose, not continuously."},
  {id:34,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Methodology",q:"What is assume-guarantee (compositional) verification?",a:"Each component is verified in isolation: Component A is proven correct assuming B's outputs satisfy a guarantee G_B; B is proven to produce G_B assuming A's outputs satisfy G_A. If both hold and the assumptions are mutually consistent, global correctness follows. Enables FV of large designs by breaking the monolithic state space into tractable pieces."},
  {id:35,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Methodology",q:"What is data path abstraction and when do you apply it?",a:"Replace wide data signals (e.g. 512-bit data buses, cache lines) with unconstrained symbolic free variables, ignoring actual data content. Applied when the property only cares about control flow (valid/ready, addresses, counts) not data values. Eliminates the data path from the COI, dramatically reducing solver complexity."},
  {id:36,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"SVA",q:"Write a mutual exclusion assertion for a 4-way arbiter.",a:"assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  $onehot0(grant));\n\n$onehot0 returns true if at most one bit is set — covers the no-grant case. Use $onehot if exactly one grant must always be active. This is cleaner than checking all pairs individually."},
  {id:37,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Methodology",q:"What are the signs a proof is not converging and what do you do?",a:"Signs: proof depth grows rapidly with no CEX and no full proof, memory usage explodes, tool oscillates between SAT calls, wall-clock timeout.\nResponse: 1) Reduce COI by splitting into smaller sub-properties. 2) Apply data path abstraction. 3) Blackbox non-essential submodules. 4) Try a different engine (PDR vs BMC). 5) Add case-split constraints. 6) Check for missing assume constraints causing over-approximation."},
  {id:38,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"SVA",q:"What is $countones and how is it used in credit or one-hot verification?",a:"$countones(vec) returns the number of bits set to 1 in vec as an integer.\nCredit tracking: assert property ($countones(outstanding_bits) <= MAX_CREDITS);\nOne-hot check: assert property ($countones(grant) == 1);\nMore expressive than $onehot for parametric or partial-count assertions."},
  {id:39,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"SVA",q:"Write a valid/ready handshake hold assertion (AXI-style).",a:"Once valid is asserted, it must not be withdrawn until ready acknowledges:\n\nassert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)\n  valid && !ready |=> valid);\n\nAlso assert data stability during the hold:\nassert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)\n  valid && !ready |=> $stable(data));"},
  {id:40,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Methodology",q:"What is formal completeness checking and what gap does it address?",a:"Checks whether the written set of assertions actually covers the design's observable behaviour — identifies signal toggles, design states, or transitions that are not captured by any property. Addresses the gap between 'all assertions pass' and 'the design is fully verified'. A clean completeness result means no observable behaviour escapes the property set."},
  {id:41,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Methodology",q:"What does 'Engine: Unknown' in JasperGold output mean?",a:"The solver terminated without reaching a conclusive result within allocated time or memory — it could neither prove nor falsify the property. This is different from an Inconclusive/bounded result (where BMC ran to depth N cleanly). Unknown means the engine hit a resource wall; it may have explored millions of states internally but still couldn't converge. Action: reduce COI, change engine mode (try PDR if BMC timed out, or vice versa), apply abstraction, or decompose the proof into smaller sub-properties."},
  {id:42,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Methodology",q:"What is invariant strengthening and when is it needed?",a:"When k-induction fails because the inductive hypothesis allows unreachable states, you add auxiliary assertions (lemmas/helper properties) that together with the original property form a stronger inductive set. The auxiliary assertions prune the unreachable states from the hypothesis space, making the inductive step provable. These helpers must themselves be proven (usually with the same technique)."},
  {id:43,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Protocols",q:"How do you approach FPV for a multi-lane interface with independent per-lane flow control?",a:"Phase 1 — per-lane isolation: verify each lane's protocol properties independently (credit, valid/ready, ordering). Reduces complexity by 1/N.\nPhase 2 — cross-lane properties: arbitration fairness, no inter-lane credit interference, aggregate bandwidth bounds.\nPhase 3 — integration: compose per-lane proofs under inter-lane assume constraints.\nAbstract all data planes. Parameterise assertions with generate blocks if lane count varies."},
  {id:44,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"SVA",q:"What is the difference between ##1 and [*1] in SVA sequences?",a:"##1 is a one-cycle delay between two events in a sequence: (a ##1 b) means a occurs, then one cycle later b occurs.\n[*1] is a consecutive repetition operator: (a [*1]) means a holds for exactly 1 consecutive cycle (equivalent to just a).\n[*N] means exactly N consecutive cycles. ##1 is about timing between distinct events; [*N] is about repetition of the same condition."},
  {id:45,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Methodology",q:"What is cover-driven convergence and why does it matter before running asserts?",a:"Before trusting assert results, prove every cover property that represents a key stimulus scenario. If a cover is Unreachable (Uncovered), your assume constraints are too restrictive and are eliminating real behaviours — any 'Proven' assert in that environment may be vacuously true. Fix constraints first, then run asserts."},
  {id:46,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Methodology",q:"What is ghost state / shadow logic in FPV?",a:"Auxiliary state added only to the formal model (never synthesised) to track information needed for property verification that isn't present in the RTL. Examples: a ghost counter tracking outstanding transactions, a symbolic data tag tracking write-data through a pipeline, a sequence number for ordering checks. Implemented via SVA local variables or auxiliary RTL in the bind file."},
  {id:47,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Methodology",q:"How do you verify data integrity (write data matches read data) without a scoreboard?",a:"Use a symbolic ghost variable approach: assume the write data is a free symbolic value 'data_sym' at a specific address 'addr_sym'. Assert that any subsequent read at 'addr_sym' returns 'data_sym'. The symbolic value acts as a one-entry implicit scoreboard. For multiple entries, use a ghost memory array indexed by address."},
  {id:48,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"Methodology",q:"What is the difference between over-constraining and under-constraining, and how do you diagnose each?",a:"Over-constraining: assume statements eliminate real behaviours, causing cover properties to fail (Uncovered) and asserts to pass vacuously. Diagnose by running cover properties — if key scenarios are Uncovered, constraints are too tight.\nUnder-constraining: the solver explores impossible inputs, generating spurious CEX. Diagnose by examining CEX waveforms — if the input sequence is physically impossible (violates protocol), a constraint is missing."},
  {id:49,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"SVA",q:"How and why do you use the `bind` construct in FPV?",a:"bind attaches an SVA module (containing properties, assumptions, and covers) to a specific RTL module instance without modifying the RTL source. This keeps verification logic completely separate from design code, allows the same property module to be reused across multiple instances, and supports per-instance sign-off. Syntax: bind dut_module property_module props_inst(.clk(clk), .sig(sig));"},
  {id:50,diff:"Intermediate",cat:"SVA",q:"What are SVA local variables and why are they useful in FPV?",a:"Local variables are declared inside a sequence or property and capture signal values at specific match points for use later in the same sequence. They enable scoreboard-like properties without RTL ghost state.\n\nLocal variables must be declared in the property scope. Correct example:\n\nproperty data_integrity;\n  logic [DATA_W-1:0] data_cap;\n  @(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)\n    (wr_valid, data_cap = wr_data) ##[1:MAX]\n    (rd_valid && rd_addr == wr_addr) |-> rd_data == data_cap;\nendproperty\n\nThe key: declare 'data_cap' as a 'logic' local variable inside the property body. The comma operator inside the sequence match item performs the capture assignment. Missing the declaration is the most common syntax error with local variables."},
  {id:51,diff:"Advanced",cat:"Algorithms",q:"How does CEGAR (Counterexample-Guided Abstraction Refinement) work?",a:"1) Start with a coarse abstraction (over-approximate). 2) Run formal verification. 3) If a CEX is found, check if it is reachable in the concrete design. 4) If spurious (unreachable in concrete), extract the reason and refine the abstraction to eliminate it. 5) Repeat until a real CEX or a proof is found. Automates the abstraction-refinement loop that engineers otherwise do manually."},
  {id:52,diff:"Advanced",cat:"Algorithms",q:"What is interpolation-based model checking?",a:"Uses Craig interpolants derived from SAT refutation proofs to compute over-approximate reachable state sets without full time-unrolling. An interpolant for an unsatisfiable BMC query at depth k summarises what cannot happen — used to build compact representations of reachable sets across arbitrary depths. Often more memory-efficient than pure PDR for certain problem classes."},
  {id:53,diff:"Advanced",cat:"Protocols",q:"How do you verify an AXI4 interface using FPV?",a:"Per-channel handshake properties for each of AW, W, B, AR, R (valid/ready hold, data stability). ID-based ordering: responses to the SAME transaction ID must be returned in order — AXI4 explicitly allows out-of-order responses across different IDs, so do not assert global response ordering. Outstanding transaction depth bounded by the FIFO sizes. Data stability between valid and handshake. Abstract all data payloads. Key challenge: circular dependency between channels (W data must follow AW address, B response follows W last) requires careful assume scoping to avoid over-constraining."},
  {id:54,diff:"Advanced",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What is a fairness constraint in liveness verification?",a:"A fairness constraint asserts that certain conditions occur infinitely often in any fair execution — e.g. the arbiter is not permanently blocked, the bus is not permanently held by one master. Without fairness, a liveness property (request eventually granted) can be trivially falsified by a path where the system is artificially starved forever."},
  {id:55,diff:"Advanced",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What is a specification gap and how does FV expose it?",a:"A specification gap is an under-specified behaviour — the spec does not define what should happen in a particular case, allowing both correct and incorrect implementations. FPV exposes gaps when a CEX demonstrates behaviour that violates engineering intuition but does not violate any written property. Forces implicit assumptions to be made explicit in either the spec or the property set."},
  {id:56,diff:"Advanced",cat:"Security",q:"What is non-interference and how do you formally verify it?",a:"Non-interference: secret inputs do not influence observable (public) outputs. Formally verified via a product construction — run two copies of the design with identical public inputs but different secret inputs. Assert that all public outputs are bit-identical across both copies. Any divergence means the secret leaked. Implemented in JasperGold SPV and academic tools like Clover."},
  {id:57,diff:"Advanced",cat:"Security",q:"What is UPEC and what class of hardware vulnerabilities does it target?",a:"Unique Program Execution Checking — formally verifies that two executions with different secret values produce identical observable microarchitectural states (cache states, branch predictor state, timing). Targets hardware side-channel vulnerabilities including Spectre, Meltdown, and related speculative execution attacks."},
  {id:58,diff:"Advanced",cat:"Core Concepts",q:"What is word-level model checking vs. bit-level model checking?",a:"Bit-level (SAT): bit-blasts all operations to Boolean variables — handles arbitrary logic but scales poorly with word width.\nWord-level (SMT with bitvectors/arrays): reasons over operations like add, multiply, comparison at the word level without bit-blasting. More efficient for arithmetic-heavy datapaths. JasperGold uses both internally, selecting based on design structure and property type."},
  {id:59,diff:"Advanced",cat:"Protocols",q:"How do you formally verify a MESI cache coherency protocol?",a:"Encode each cache line's MESI state symbolically. Key invariants to assert: at most one Modified state per address across all caches; at most one Exclusive state per address; multiple Shared states are allowed; when a line is in M state, memory is stale (data consistency). Challenge: N-cache state space — use parametric verification or cutoff theorems (prove for N=2 implies all N under certain conditions)."},
  {id:60,diff:"Advanced",cat:"Methodology",q:"What is parametric formal verification and how does it scale?",a:"Proves properties that hold for ANY value of a design parameter (e.g. N lanes, M credit depth). Techniques: symbolic parameter encoding, induction over N (base case N=1, step: if true for k, prove for k+1), or cutoff theorems for specific protocol classes where proving for a small fixed N implies all N. Fully parametric proofs are rare; most industrial work uses bounded parametric checks."},
  {id:101,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"What is the JasperGold FPV App workflow from TCL?",a:"Correct JasperGold FPV TCL flow:\n\nanalyze -sv05 {rtl/design.sv props/props.sv}\nelaborate -top tb_top\nclock clk\nreset -expression {!rst_n}\ncheck_property -init\nreport_property\n\nKey points:\n- 'clock clk' sets the primary clock.\n- 'reset -expression {!rst_n}' tells JasperGold the active-low reset condition and handles initial state — do NOT add a separate assume locking rst_n=0, which would prevent the design ever leaving reset.\n- 'check_property -init' runs all loaded properties.\n- Use 'check_property -name {prop1 prop2}' to target specific properties during debug.\n- 'report_property' prints Proven/Falsified/Inconclusive per property."},
  {id:102,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"What is the JasperGold Connectivity Check (CC) App?",a:"Verifies structural wiring correctness against a golden netlist or connection spec — catches unintended disconnects, floating nets, and incorrect signal routing. Does not require user-written SVA properties. Typically run post-integration (after stitching subsystems) to catch integration wiring bugs before simulation testbenches are ready."},
  {id:103,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"What does the JasperGold Unreachability App report?",a:"Formally proves which RTL code is dead — never reachable under any valid stimulus. Reports: always-false branches, always-constant signals, unreachable FSM states, dead always blocks. Critical for security audits (dead safety checks that were never reachable) and for excluding dead code from coverage goals."},
  {id:104,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"What is JasperGold Superlint and how does it go beyond standard linting?",a:"Superlint uses formal analysis to detect violations that pure syntax/static linters miss: X-propagation paths that reach outputs, unreachable code that static linters flag as live, unintended clock domain crossings in the data path, reset domain violations. The formal engine proves or disproves each lint rule rather than pattern-matching — zero false positives on formally disproven rules."},
  {id:105,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"What is JasperGold Security Path Verification (SPV)?",a:"SPV formally verifies information flow: proves that high-security (secret) signals cannot influence low-security (observable) outputs. Uses formal taint propagation — marks secret signals and proves the taint cannot reach public observation points. Detects unintended hardware backdoors, key leakage paths, and covert channels."},
  {id:106,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"What is the JasperGold AutoFormal App and what is its output limitation?",a:"Automatically generates SVA properties from the RTL using structural analysis and data mining — no user spec required. Useful for generating a starter property set when specs are incomplete. Critical limitation: AutoFormal properties describe what the design DOES, not what it SHOULD DO. They cannot catch bugs that are consistently present in the RTL — all AutoFormal properties will pass on a buggy design that implements its bugs consistently."},
  {id:107,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"What does set_engine_mode do in JasperGold and what are the key modes?",a:"Controls which proof engines are launched.\nKey modes:\n  set_engine_mode Ht       — PDR/IC3 only (best for proof convergence)\n  set_engine_mode Bmc      — BMC only (fast bug-hunting, no proof)\n  set_engine_mode {Ht Bmc} — PDR and BMC in parallel (default portfolio)\n  set_engine_mode All      — launch all available engines\nPortfolio mode returns whichever engine completes first. Different engines suit different property types — no single engine dominates all cases."},
  {id:108,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"What does set_max_trace_length do and which engines does it affect?",a:"Limits the BMC unrolling depth (number of cycles explored by the BMC engine). Increase when deep protocol sequences are suspected. Decrease for a fast initial bug sweep.\nIMPORTANT: set_max_trace_length has NO effect on PDR/IC3 (Ht mode) — that engine is depth-independent by design. Setting it is only relevant when BMC is active in the engine portfolio."},
  {id:109,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"How do you run a JasperGold FPV regression in batch/CI mode?",a:"Invoke JasperGold non-interactively:\n\njaspergold -batch run_fpv.tcl\n\nExit code 0 = all properties proven/bounded per criteria. Non-zero = failures. In CI (Jenkins/GitLab):\n1) Run jaspergold -batch as a pipeline step.\n2) Parse the report_property output or XML results for Falsified/Unknown counts.\n3) Fail the pipeline on any Falsified result.\n4) Archive CEX waveforms as pipeline artefacts for engineer triage."},
  {id:110,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"How do you apply assumptions only during specific cycle ranges in JasperGold?",a:"JasperGold has no built-in -time {start end} flag on assume, and $time_steps is NOT a valid SVA system function. The correct approach is to use a ghost cycle counter driven by auxiliary RTL or an SVA sequence with a counter:\n\n// Ghost counter approach in the bind/property file:\nlogic [7:0] cyc_cnt;\nalways_ff @(posedge clk or negedge rst_n)\n  if (!rst_n) cyc_cnt <= 0;\n  else cyc_cnt <= cyc_cnt + 1;\n\n// Then constrain only for early cycles:\nassume property (@(posedge clk) cyc_cnt < 5 |-> !rst_n);\n\nAlternatively, use $fell(rst_n) and ##N delays to scope assumptions relative to reset deassertion."},
  {id:111,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"What does report_cov output in JasperGold?",a:"Reports formal cover property results per property:\n  Covered: a reachability witness was found (with trace)\n  Uncovered: the scenario is unreachable (formally proven unreachable or not explored)\nUncovered covers are actionable: either the design intentionally cannot reach that state (dead scenario) or an assume constraint is incorrectly blocking it. Always investigate Uncovered covers before signing off asserts."},
  {id:112,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"What is set_proofgrid in JasperGold?",a:"Enables multi-core parallel proof execution on the local machine. When running multiple properties, JasperGold can dispatch them across available CPU cores simultaneously rather than sequentially.\n\nset_proofgrid -max_local_jobs 8\n\nFor distributed compute (LSF/Grid), JasperGold uses separate job submission infrastructure — set_proofgrid itself is local-core parallelism only."},
  {id:113,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"What is the difference between check_property and prove_property in JasperGold?",a:"check_property: verifies a specific named property or explicit list. Use during debug to target individual failing properties.\ncheck_property -init: runs ALL currently loaded properties in the environment — this is the correct command for full regression, not 'prove_property' which is not a standard JasperGold TCL command.\n\nIn practice:\n  Debug:     check_property -name {prop_a prop_b}\n  Regression: check_property -init\n\nAfter running, use report_property to print status, or get_property_list -include_status {Falsified} for automated triage."},
  {id:114,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"How do you filter property results programmatically in JasperGold TCL?",a:"Use get_property_list with status filters:\n\nset failed [get_property_list -include_status {Falsified}]\nset unknown [get_property_list -include_status {Unknown}]\nforeach p $failed { puts \"FAILED: $p\" }\n\nThis enables automated triage scripts that file bugs for Falsified properties, escalate Unknowns, and generate sign-off reports — no manual result parsing needed."},
  {id:115,diff:"Jasper",cat:"Jasper Apps",q:"What is the JasperGold Formal Verification App for X-propagation (XPROP)?",a:"JasperGold's Superlint and dedicated X-semantic apps formally analyse how unknown (X) values propagate through the design from undefined initial states or uninitialized memories. They prove whether any X can reach a design output or a state-holding element under valid stimulus. Critical for low-power designs where power-gated domains produce X on wakeup."},
  {id:116,diff:"Coverage",cat:"Coverage",q:"What is the difference between functional coverage and formal cover properties?",a:"Functional coverage (SVA covergroups, coverpoints in simulation): statistical — measures how many of a defined set of stimulus scenarios were exercised across random/directed tests. Formal cover properties: exhaustive — mathematically proves or disproves reachability. A formal 'Covered' result means the scenario is definitely reachable; an 'Uncovered' means it is formally proven unreachable."},
  {id:117,diff:"Coverage",cat:"Coverage",q:"What is toggle coverage and how does formal verification help with it?",a:"Toggle coverage tracks whether each signal bit has transitioned both 0→1 and 1→0 during verification. Formal tools complement simulation toggle coverage by formally proving which toggles are impossible (dead signals) — those should be excluded from coverage goals rather than chased with simulation. Eliminates wasted effort on unreachable toggle goals."},
  {id:118,diff:"Coverage",cat:"Coverage",q:"List the main types of code coverage in an RTL verification flow.",a:"Statement/line coverage: each executable statement reached.\nBranch coverage: each if/case branch taken (both directions).\nCondition coverage: each sub-expression in compound conditions evaluated T and F independently.\nFSM coverage: each state entered and each transition taken.\nToggle coverage: each signal bit toggled both directions.\nExpression coverage: each unique combination of sub-conditions.\nFormal can prove unreachability for any of these."},
  {id:119,diff:"Coverage",cat:"Coverage",q:"What is formal coverage closure vs. simulation coverage closure?",a:"Formal closure: all cover properties are proven reachable AND formal unreachability analysis proves that all remaining uncovered code is genuinely dead. Mathematically complete for the property set.\nSimulation closure: enough tests run to hit coverage goals statistically (typically 95-100% of enabled goals). Requires human judgment on exclusion lists and coverage thresholds. Neither is superior — they are complementary."},
  {id:120,diff:"Coverage",cat:"Coverage",q:"How does JasperGold identify which coverage goals are formally unreachable?",a:"The Unreachability App formally proves whether each coverage goal (branch, toggle, FSM state) is reachable under any valid stimulus. Goals proven Unreachable are genuine dead code — safe to exclude from the coverage database. Goals proven Reachable provide a target for simulation. This eliminates false coverage holes."},
  {id:121,diff:"Coverage",cat:"Coverage",q:"What is COI-based coverage analysis and why does it matter?",a:"After a formal proof run, JasperGold reports which signals fall within the COI of each property (influence the proof) and which are outside it. Signals outside the COI are irrelevant to that property's correctness — coverage goals on those signals should not be attributed to that property's verification. Prevents artificial coverage inflation and reveals which modules are not covered by any property."},
  {id:122,diff:"Coverage",cat:"Coverage",q:"What is the relationship between cover properties and verification completeness?",a:"Cover properties define what must be demonstrably possible — they are the behavioural completeness specification of the FPV environment. A property set where every cover is formally proven reachable AND no observable design behaviour falls outside the COI of some assert is as close to complete verification as FPV can achieve without a full spec formalisation."},
  {id:123,diff:"Coverage",cat:"Coverage",q:"How do you write FSM state and transition coverage properties in SVA?",a:"State reachability cover:\n  cover property (@(posedge clk) state == S_GRANT);\n\nTransition cover:\n  cover property (@(posedge clk)\n    state == S_IDLE ##1 state == S_ARBIT);\n\nRun as formal covers — Uncovered result means that FSM state/transition is formally unreachable, which is either a dead state (bug) or should be excluded from coverage goals."},
  {id:124,diff:"Coverage",cat:"Coverage",q:"What is vacuity checking and how does it relate to coverage completeness?",a:"Vacuity checking formally verifies that the antecedent of each assert actually fires at least once under the applied constraints. A vacuously-passing assertion contributes zero verification value — it never exercises the consequent. JasperGold generates a companion cover property for each assert's trigger condition. Any assertion whose trigger cover is Uncovered is vacuous and must be investigated."},
  {id:125,diff:"Coverage",cat:"Coverage",q:"How do you measure and improve property coverage completeness in an FPV flow?",a:"1) Run formal completeness analysis (e.g. JasperGold's completeness check) to identify unobserved signal toggles and unreached states.\n2) Check vacuity of all asserts via companion covers.\n3) For each uncovered behaviour, either write a new property covering it or formally prove it is dead code.\n4) Track mutation score — surviving mutants reveal property granularity gaps.\n5) Sign off only when completeness analysis is clean and mutation score meets threshold."},
  {id:126,diff:"Mutation",cat:"Mutation Testing",q:"What is mutation testing in hardware verification?",a:"Injects small, targeted RTL changes (mutants) — e.g. flipping an operator, changing a constant — and checks whether the verification suite (formal properties or simulation tests) detects each change. Killed mutant = verification detected the change. Survived mutant = the change was undetected, exposing a verification gap."},
  {id:127,diff:"Mutation",cat:"Mutation Testing",q:"What are common RTL mutation operators?",a:"Constant bit-flip: 1'b0 → 1'b1 and vice versa.\nOperator replacement: + → -, && → ||, < → <=.\nSignal substitution: replace signal A with signal B or with constant 0/1.\nOff-by-one on comparators: == to !=, < to <=.\nBit-width change: [7:0] → [6:0].\nClock edge flip: posedge → negedge.\nFSM next-state substitution: replace one state encoding with another."},
  {id:128,diff:"Mutation",cat:"Mutation Testing",q:"What is a mutation score and how is it calculated?",a:"Mutation score = (killed mutants ÷ total non-equivalent mutants) × 100%.\nA mutant is killed when the verification suite produces a failure (CEX or assertion violation) on the mutant design.\nEquivalent mutants (changes that produce identical observable behaviour) are excluded from the denominator — they are impossible to kill and skew the score."},
  {id:129,diff:"Mutation",cat:"Mutation Testing",q:"How does formal mutation analysis differ from simulation-based mutation testing?",a:"Formal: inject mutant, rerun FPV on existing property set. If all properties still prove (or the same ones prove), mutant survived — formal exhaustively confirmed the property set cannot distinguish the mutant from the original. No test vectors needed.\nSimulation: requires a specific test sequence to exercise the mutated path. Incomplete — a mutant survives if no existing test happens to trigger and observe the change.\nFormal mutation analysis gives a stronger kill guarantee per property."},
  {id:130,diff:"Mutation",cat:"Mutation Testing",q:"What is JasperGold's formal mutation analysis capability?",a:"JasperGold's formal mutation analysis (available through the FPV App mutation mode) can systematically apply RTL mutants and re-run the property set on each. Survived mutants are reported with the specific RTL change that was undetected. These directly guide property improvement: each survived mutant tells you exactly what behaviour the property set fails to distinguish.\nNote: this is distinct from simulation-based mutation tools (vManager mutation campaign) which rely on simulation for kill detection."},
  {id:131,diff:"Mutation",cat:"Mutation Testing",q:"What is the difference between equivalent mutants and survived mutants?",a:"Equivalent mutant: the injected RTL change produces identical observable behaviour to the original for all possible inputs — formally, the mutant and original are behaviourally equivalent. Cannot be killed. Must be identified and excluded from the mutation score denominator.\nSurvived mutant: the change is observable in principle, but no test or property caught it — a real verification gap requiring new properties."},
  {id:132,diff:"Mutation",cat:"Mutation Testing",q:"How do you use mutation testing results to improve an FPV property set?",a:"1) Identify the survived mutant's RTL change.\n2) Determine what behaviour the change would alter.\n3) Write a cover property confirming that behaviour is observable (reachable and the signal toggles).\n4) Write an assert that captures the correct expected behaviour.\n5) Re-run mutation analysis — confirm the mutant is now killed.\n6) Add the new property to the regression."},
  {id:133,diff:"Mutation",cat:"Mutation Testing",q:"What is weak vs. strong mutation testing?",a:"Strong mutation: a mutant is killed only if the verification suite produces a different external output or assertion violation — the mutant must affect an observable output.\nWeak mutation: killed if the mutant produces a different internal state at the mutation point, regardless of whether it propagates to an observable output.\nFormal tools implement strong mutation semantics — only kills where the property set observes a difference count."},
  {id:134,diff:"Mutation",cat:"Mutation Testing",q:"How do you handle scalability of mutation testing on large RTL designs?",a:"1) Scope mutations to high-risk modules: FSMs, protocol handlers, credit counters, arbiters.\n2) COI pruning: skip mutants on signals outside the COI of all properties — they cannot affect any observable output.\n3) Parallel execution: use proofgrid or LSF to run mutant checks in parallel.\n4) Prioritise mutation operators by historical bug distribution — operator replacement and off-by-one are highest yield.\n5) Use simulation-based mutation for large datapaths; formal mutation for control logic."},
  {id:135,diff:"Mutation",cat:"Mutation Testing",q:"What is the relationship between mutation score and formal coverage metrics?",a:"They measure complementary things. High formal coverage (all asserts proven, all covers hit) means the property set is logically consistent and complete for defined scenarios — but says nothing about granularity. High mutation score means the properties are fine-grained enough to detect small RTL deviations. A design can have 100% formal coverage and a poor mutation score if properties are too coarsely specified."},
  {id:200,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"What is wrong with this assertion?",code:"assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  req |-> ack);",a:"Two bugs:\n1) No `disable iff (!rst_n)` — the assertion fires during reset when ack may legitimately be low, causing spurious failures on every reset cycle.\n2) |-> checks ack the SAME cycle as req. For most request/acknowledge protocols, ack arrives at least one cycle after req (should be |=> or ##[1:N])."},
  {id:201,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"What is wrong with this credit counter property?",code:"assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  credit_count >= 0);",a:"credit_count is almost certainly declared as an unsigned type (logic [N:0]). Unsigned signals are always >= 0 in SystemVerilog — this assertion is trivially and vacuously true for an unsigned type. It will never catch a credit underflow wrapping to a large positive value.\nFix: assert that credit_count never wraps — check for the decrement-when-zero condition:\nassert property (credit_count == 0 |-> !consume);"},
  {id:202,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"Find the bug in this one-hot arbiter assertion.",code:"assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  grant[0] || grant[1] || grant[2] || grant[3]);",a:"Two problems:\n1) This asserts that at least one grant is always active — but the arbiter may legitimately issue no grant when no request is pending. This will fail during idle cycles.\n2) It does NOT check mutual exclusion — two grants can be simultaneously active and this assertion still passes.\nFix: assert $onehot0(grant) for mutual exclusion (allowing no-grant), and separately cover that each grant fires."},
  {id:203,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"What is wrong with this reset property?",code:"assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  !rst_n |-> (state == IDLE && count == 0));",a:"This checks that WHEN reset is low, state and count are correct — but it checks a combinational condition on outputs sampled at the clock edge DURING reset. The real intent is usually to check that outputs are correct ONE CYCLE AFTER reset deasserts (i.e. after the reset flops have propagated).\nFix:\nassert property (@(posedge clk)\n  $rose(rst_n) |=> (state == IDLE && count == 0));\nAlso missing disable iff on other assertions that should be suspended during reset."},
  {id:204,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"What is wrong with this FIFO not-full check?",code:"assume property (@(posedge clk)\n  !full |-> push_en);",a:"The assume is backwards — it says 'whenever NOT full, a push MUST happen'. This forces the environment to push on every non-full cycle, eliminating all scenarios where the FIFO sits idle. The real constraint should limit when pushes CAN happen, not force pushes at every opportunity.\nThis over-constraints the environment, making the full/overflow cover properties Uncovered and masking any real overflow bug.\nFix: assume property (!full || !push_en) — cannot push when full, but free to push or not push otherwise."},
  {id:205,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"What is wrong with this sequence?",code:"sequence req_to_ack;\n  req ##[1:5] ack;\nendsequence\n\nassert property (@(posedge clk)\n  req_to_ack);",a:"Two real issues:\n1) Missing implication — a bare 'assert property (req ##[1:5] ack)' attempts to start a match every clock cycle. When req is low, the match attempt immediately fails and the property passes vacuously for that cycle. This means the property NEVER actually checks anything when req is low — it only checks ack when req happens to be high. The fix is to make the intent explicit with an implication: assert property (@(posedge clk) req |-> ##[1:5] ack); This clearly states: IF req is high, THEN ack must arrive within 5 cycles.\n2) No disable iff for reset — the property fires during reset, causing spurious failures if ack cannot be guaranteed during the reset sequence."},
  {id:206,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"What is wrong with this data stability assertion?",code:"assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  valid |-> $stable(data));",a:"$stable(data) checks that data is the same as the PREVIOUS cycle. This is checking that data hasn't changed since last cycle whenever valid is high — but this fails on the FIRST cycle valid goes high (data may have been anything before).\nThe intent is usually to hold data stable while valid is high AND ready is low:\nassert property (@(posedge clk)\n  valid && !ready |=> $stable(data));\nAlso no disable iff for reset."},
  {id:207,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"What is wrong with this cover property used to validate the environment?",code:"cover property (@(posedge clk)\n  1'b1);",a:"'cover property (1'b1)' is always true — it trivially covers every clock cycle. It tells you nothing useful about whether your environment allows meaningful stimulus. This is a placeholder that was left in accidentally.\nA useful cover property must specify an actual scenario: e.g. a specific state reached, a specific signal transition, or a multi-cycle sequence. Covering 1'b1 will always show as 'Covered' and gives false confidence that the environment was validated."},
  {id:208,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"What is wrong with this vacuity-prone property?",code:"assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  (state == GRANT && req && !timeout && !cancel\n   && priority_override && !flush) |-> ack);",a:"The antecedent has so many conditions ANDed together that it may never trigger — it is highly likely to be vacuously true. The tool will report 'Proven' but the property has never actually checked ack.\nRed flag: complex multi-condition antecedents with 5+ signals.\nDiagnosis: add a companion cover property: cover property (state == GRANT && req && !timeout && !cancel && priority_override && !flush);\nIf that cover is Uncovered, the assert is vacuous. Simplify or split the antecedent."},
  {id:209,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"What is wrong with this counter overflow property?",code:"assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  count == MAX_COUNT |-> count == 0);",a:"This checks that in the SAME cycle count == MAX_COUNT, count is also == 0. That is a contradiction — count cannot simultaneously equal MAX_COUNT and 0 (unless MAX_COUNT == 0).\nThe intent is to check that the cycle AFTER reaching MAX_COUNT, the counter wraps to 0:\nassert property (@(posedge clk)\n  count == MAX_COUNT |=> count == 0);\nUsing |-> instead of |=> is one of the most common SVA timing bugs."},
  {id:210,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"What is wrong with this assume constraint on a bus?",code:"assume property (@(posedge clk)\n  $onehot(req));",a:"Assuming req is always one-hot means the formal environment can NEVER explore the case where req == 0 (no requests) or multiple requests simultaneously. This over-constrains the stimulus.\nConsequences:\n1) No-request idle behaviour is never verified.\n2) Arbitration under simultaneous requests is excluded.\n3) Cover properties for idle state will be Uncovered.\nFix: assume $onehot0(req) to allow no-request cycles, and separately verify arbitration logic handles simultaneous requests with its own properties rather than excluding them."},
  {id:211,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"What is the problem with this FSM property?",code:"assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  state != ERROR);",a:"This asserts the ERROR state is never reached — which may be the intent, but there are two issues:\n1) If ERROR is a legitimate recovery state (entered on protocol violation, then recovered from), this assertion incorrectly flags valid behaviour.\n2) More critically, if this assertion is wrong and the design SHOULD be able to enter ERROR under fault injection, this is an over-specification that masks a real design requirement.\nAlways pair such assertions with a spec reference. Also: missing disable iff during reset — reset may pass through ERROR transiently."},
  {id:212,diff:"Bug",cat:"Spot the Bug",q:"What is wrong with this attempt to model a synchroniser in FPV?",code:"// Two-flop synchroniser model\nassume property (@(posedge clk_dst)\n  sync_out == $past(sync_in, 2));",a:"This models a fixed deterministic 2-cycle delay, which is not how a real synchroniser works. When a signal crosses a clock domain boundary, the first capture flop may enter metastability — an undefined analogue state where the output is neither a clean 0 nor 1. The second flop resolves this, but the resolved value may be 0 or 1 regardless of what sync_in was; it is non-deterministic with respect to the source clock domain.\nThe assume is therefore wrong in two ways: (1) it constrains sync_out to a specific value (past input), eliminating the non-determinism that is fundamental to CDC behaviour; (2) $past(sync_in, 2) samples sync_in on clk_dst, but sync_in is driven by clk_src — this is sampling a CDC signal on the wrong clock, which is itself a modelling error.\nCorrect approach: model sync_out as a free variable constrained only to be stable after the synchronisation window, and use a dedicated CDC formal app rather than hand-rolled assumes."}
,
  {id:301,diff:"SVA_Deep",cat:"SVA Deep Dive",q:"What does the `throughout` operator do in SVA?",a:"req_active throughout ##[1:10] ack\nMeans: req_active must hold TRUE for every cycle of the entire sequence — from the start through to the point ack fires. It is not just a precondition; it is a continuous constraint over the whole sequence window.\nCommon use: asserting a request signal stays asserted while waiting for an acknowledgement. If req_active drops at any point during the [1:10] window, the property fails."},
  {id:302,diff:"SVA_Deep",cat:"SVA Deep Dive",q:"What is the difference between `and` and `intersect` on SVA sequences?",a:"Both require two sequences to match simultaneously, but they differ on length:\n\nand: both sequences must match, but they can be different lengths. The overall match ends when BOTH have completed (the longer one wins).\n\nintersect: both sequences must match AND must end at exactly the same cycle. If the lengths differ, intersect fails.\n\nExample:\n  (a ##[1:5] b) intersect (##3 c)  — b and c must both occur at cycle 4 (exactly).\n  (a ##[1:5] b) and     (##3 c)  — b at some point 1-5, c at cycle 4, sequence ends when both done."},
  {id:303,diff:"SVA_Deep",cat:"SVA Deep Dive",q:"What does `first_match` do and when do you need it?",a:"first_match(seq) causes the sequence to match only on the FIRST (earliest) completion point and discards all later possible matches.\n\nWithout it, SVA sequences are non-deterministic — a sequence like (a ##[1:3] b) can match at cycle 1, 2, or 3 after a. All branches are explored.\n\nfirst_match is useful when you want to capture data at the first possible match point using local variables, and you don't want later matches overwriting the capture:\n\n(first_match(req ##[1:5] ack), data_cap = data) |-> check_data"},
  {id:304,diff:"SVA_Deep",cat:"SVA Deep Dive",q:"What is the `within` operator in SVA?",a:"seq1 within seq2 means: seq1 must match entirely within the time span of seq2. seq2 defines a window, and seq1 must start and complete inside that window.\n\nExample:\n  (start ##[1:10] end) within (enable [*1:$])\nMeans: the start-to-end sequence must happen while enable is continuously high throughout.\n\nLess commonly used than throughout but useful for windowed protocol checks."},
  {id:305,diff:"SVA_Deep",cat:"SVA Deep Dive",q:"What is the difference between sequence `and` vs property `and` in SVA?",a:"Sequence `and`: both sequences must match concurrently (used in sequence context, checked structurally).\n\nProperty `and`: both properties must hold. If either fails, the combined property fails. Used to combine independent properties into one:\n  property combined;\n    prop_a and prop_b;\n  endproperty\n\nThis is semantically different — property and is a logical AND of two separate obligations evaluated independently, not a structural concurrent sequence match."},
  {id:306,diff:"SVA_Deep",cat:"SVA Deep Dive",q:"What does `$sampled` do and how does it differ from reading a signal directly in SVA?",a:"$sampled(expr) explicitly uses the sampled value of a signal — the value captured at the previous active clock edge (the 'observed' region in the SV scheduling semantics).\n\nIn concurrent SVA properties, signals are already sampled automatically at the clock edge, so $sampled is usually redundant. However it matters in:\n1) Checker modules where you mix procedural and concurrent code\n2) Preventing read-during-update races in complex always blocks\n3) Making the sampling intent explicit for documentation\n\nKey difference from $past: $sampled(x) and $past(x,1) are NOT the same. $sampled(x) gives the value of x at the current clock edge (sampled in the preponed region — before any active assignments). $past(x,1) gives the value from one clock cycle ago. In practice, $sampled is about scheduling region semantics, not temporal lookback."},
  {id:307,diff:"SVA_Deep",cat:"SVA Deep Dive",q:"How do you write a parameterised SVA property that works for any N-wide bus?",a:"Use a generate block or a module parameter:\n\nmodule props #(parameter N=4) (input clk, rst_n, input [N-1:0] grant);\n  // One-hot constraint scales with N\n  ap_onehot: assert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)\n    $onehot0(grant));\n\n  // Per-bit cover scales with generate\n  genvar i;\n  generate\n    for (i=0; i<N; i++) begin : gen_cov\n      cp_grant: cover property (@(posedge clk) grant[i]);\n    end\n  endgenerate\nendmodule\n\nBind it parametrically: bind dut props #(.N(NUM_LANES)) p(.clk,.rst_n,.grant);"},
  {id:308,diff:"SVA_Deep",cat:"SVA Deep Dive",q:"What is a multi-clocked SVA property and what are the restrictions?",a:"SVA allows properties that span multiple clock domains using the @() operator per sequence:\n\nproperty cdc_handshake;\n  @(posedge clk_src) req |=>\n  @(posedge clk_dst) ##[1:4] ack;\nendproperty\n\nRestrictions:\n1) Each sequence segment must have its own clock.\n2) The tool must model both clocks — both must be declared via the `clock` command.\n3) JasperGold handles multi-clock properties but they can significantly increase state space.\n4) The sampling semantics at the boundary are tool-specific — read the tool's multi-clock SV handling docs carefully.\n5) Better to use dedicated CDC formal apps for actual CDC verification rather than hand-rolling multi-clock SVA."},
  {id:309,diff:"SVA_Deep",cat:"SVA Deep Dive",q:"What is the `or` operator on sequences and how does it differ from `|` in a condition?",a:"Sequence `or` means EITHER sequence can match — non-deterministically, any completion satisfies the property:\n\n(req_a ##[1:3] ack_a) or (req_b ##[1:3] ack_b)\n\nThis says: either the req_a->ack_a handshake happens within 3 cycles, OR the req_b->ack_b handshake happens — whichever occurs.\n\nThis is fundamentally different from:\n  (req_a || req_b) |-> ack   — which is a boolean OR in the antecedent condition\n\nSequence `or` allows alternative TEMPORAL paths, not just alternative boolean conditions at a single point."},
  {id:310,diff:"SVA_Deep",cat:"SVA Deep Dive",q:"How do you write a property that checks a signal eventually becomes high (liveness-style) in bounded FPV?",a:"True liveness (eventually) is unbounded and requires omega-regular model checking. In bounded FPV you approximate with a bounded eventually:\n\nassert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)\n  req |-> ##[1:MAX_LATENCY] ack);\n\nMAX_LATENCY must be derived from the spec — e.g. a protocol spec guaranteeing ack within 16 cycles means MAX_LATENCY=16.\n\nThis gives you a bounded liveness guarantee: the tool proves ack arrives within MAX_LATENCY or finds a CEX. It does NOT prove unbounded liveness — if the real maximum latency is unbounded, this check will either vacuously pass (if MAX_LATENCY is too small to reach the bug) or need a full liveness proof with fairness constraints."},
  // ===================== DEBUGGING FPV FAILURES =====================
  {id:401,diff:"Debug",cat:"Debugging FPV",q:"Your assertion is proven but you suspect it might be vacuous. Walk through how you debug it.",a:"Step 1: Write a companion cover property on the antecedent trigger:\n  cover property (@(posedge clk) <antecedent condition>);\n\nStep 2: Run. If the cover is Uncovered, the antecedent never fired — the assertion is vacuously proven and worthless.\n\nStep 3: Investigate why the antecedent can't fire:\n  a) Is an assume constraint blocking the input pattern needed?\n  b) Is the antecedent condition itself impossible given RTL behaviour?\n  c) Is the reset sequence preventing the design from reaching the state?\n\nStep 4: Fix the constraint or the property. Re-run the cover. Only trust the assert once the cover is Covered.\n\nJasperGold automates step 1 with vacuity checking — run 'check_vacuity' after check_property."},
  {id:402,diff:"Debug",cat:"Debugging FPV",q:"You get a CEX but it looks physically impossible — the stimulus violates your protocol. How do you debug it?",a:"This is under-constraining: the solver is exploring inputs that can never occur in the real system.\n\nDebug process:\n1) Load the CEX waveform in the tool or simulator. Find the first cycle where the stimulus violates your protocol expectation.\n2) Write an assume property capturing that constraint. Example: if the CEX shows push_en high when full, add: assume property (full |-> !push_en);\n3) Re-run. If the CEX disappears, the constraint was missing. If a different CEX appears, investigate that one.\n4) Before adding, write a cover to confirm the assume is not too tight:\n  cover property (!full ##1 push_en);  // make sure valid push can still happen\n5) Repeat until CEX is a real bug or all spurious paths are eliminated.\n\nNever just add assumes blindly — each one narrows the proof space and risks vacuity."},
  {id:403,diff:"Debug",cat:"Debugging FPV",q:"Your cover property is Uncovered (Unreachable) but you know the scenario should be possible. How do you debug it?",a:"Uncovered covers = the assume constraints are blocking the scenario, OR the design genuinely cannot reach it.\n\nDebug process:\n1) Simplify the cover to a single condition: cover property (signal_x == VAL); — find the earliest point in the chain that's unreachable.\n2) Check if any assume is constraining signal_x or its drivers. Use 'report_assumptions' or grep your property file.\n3) Temporarily remove assumes one at a time (risky — may cause spurious CEX, but useful for isolation).\n4) Try reaching the scenario manually: trace the RTL logic and identify which assume is blocking the path.\n5) If the design genuinely can't reach it: that's dead code. Formally confirm with the Unreachability App and exclude from coverage.\n6) Check reset: is the initial state preventing the design from ever getting there? May need more reset cycles."},
  {id:404,diff:"Debug",cat:"Debugging FPV",q:"Your proof is not converging — depth keeps climbing with no CEX and no proof. What is your systematic response?",a:"Triage in order of effort:\n\n1) Check COI size: is it reasonable? Use 'report_coi' — if it's huge, the property is touching too much state.\n   Fix: split the property into smaller focused sub-properties.\n\n2) Apply data path abstraction: are wide data buses (64-bit, 256-bit) in the COI? Replace with free variables.\n\n3) Blackbox non-critical submodules: memories, FIFOs already verified elsewhere.\n\n4) Change engine: if running {Ht Bmc}, try Ht-only (PDR) — sometimes BMC prevents PDR from converging. Try 'set_engine_mode Ht'.\n\n5) Add strengthening invariants: a helper assert that prunes unreachable states can unlock k-induction.\n\n6) Case split: add assume constraints that split the proof into exhaustive sub-cases (e.g., assume count<MAX/2, prove; then assume count>=MAX/2, prove).\n\n7) If still stuck: take a bounded result at the max tractable depth, document it, and flag for architectural discussion."},
  {id:405,diff:"Debug",cat:"Debugging FPV",q:"How do you detect and debug contradictory assumptions in an FPV environment?",a:"Contradictory assumes let the solver prove ANYTHING — including trivially false properties. This is the most dangerous silent failure in FPV.\n\nDetection:\n1) Write a cover property on a condition you know must be reachable:\n   cover property (1'b1);  — if this is Uncovered, your assumes are contradictory.\n2) Write covers on basic expected behaviours: cover property (state == IDLE); — if your normal initial state is unreachable, assumes are contradictory.\n3) JasperGold: run 'check_assumptions' — it actively checks assume consistency.\n\nDebugging:\n1) Remove assumes one at a time until the cover becomes reachable again — identifies the culprit.\n2) Check for temporal contradictions: two assumes that together force a cycle-by-cycle impossibility.\n3) Common cause: reset assume forces rst_n==0 forever (covers the assume -name reset_seq mistake — never lock rst_n permanently).\n4) Check: are assume conditions mutually exclusive with realistic input patterns?"},
  {id:406,diff:"Debug",cat:"Debugging FPV",q:"A property that was Proven in a previous run is now Falsified after an RTL change. The designer says the RTL change was unrelated. How do you triage?",a:"Do not just trust 'unrelated'. The formal tool is correct.\n\n1) Load the new CEX. Identify which signals in the waveform changed behaviour relative to the old RTL.\n2) Use 'report_coi' — if the changed signal is NOT in the COI of the failing property, something else changed (check: was the property file also modified?).\n3) If the changed signal IS in the COI: the designer's change affected this property's proof. Show them the waveform and trace the dependency.\n4) Check for accidental changes: parameter modifications, port name changes, or ifdef changes that altered connectivity.\n5) Bisect if needed: check out intermediate RTL revisions to isolate which specific commit introduced the failure.\n6) Document: update the regression baseline only after root-cause is confirmed — never mark a newly Falsified property as 'expected'."},
  {id:407,diff:"Debug",cat:"Debugging FPV",q:"How do you debug a CEX that seems to violate reset — the tool shows a bad state at cycle 0?",a:"Cycle-0 issues mean the initial state is not being properly constrained.\n\nCauses and fixes:\n1) Reset constraint missing or wrong: verify 'reset -expression {!rst_n}' is correct and the signal name matches the RTL port.\n2) Reset duration too short: the design needs multiple cycles in reset to propagate to a known state. Add:\n   assume property (@(posedge clk) cyc_cnt < RST_CYCLES |-> !rst_n);\n3) Reset doesn't actually initialize all state: some FFs may have no reset (intentional or bug). Identify them with Superlint/lint and add initial value assumptions or fix the RTL.\n4) Asynchronous reset not modelled correctly: if rst_n is async, JasperGold needs to know it applies outside the clock edge.\n5) Initial value assumptions needed: for state bits without hardware reset, add:\n   assume property (@(posedge clk) $past(cyc_cnt,1)==0 |-> state==IDLE);"},
  {id:408,diff:"Debug",cat:"Debugging FPV",q:"Your CEX has depth 847. How do you make it actionable?",a:"A 847-cycle CEX is unusable directly. You need to:\n\n1) Try to reproduce at shorter depth: add 'set_max_trace_length 50' and re-run BMC. If BMC finds a shallower path to the same violation, use that.\n\n2) Examine the END of the waveform first — the last ~10 cycles before the violation. Identify what conditions directly caused the assertion failure. Work backwards from there.\n\n3) Check if the depth is real: is the protocol genuinely requiring 847 cycles to reach a corner case, or is the design stuck in a loop? Count distinct state patterns in the waveform.\n\n4) Simplify the model: apply more abstraction (blackbox, data abstraction) and re-run — the bug may surface at much shorter depth with fewer distractors.\n\n5) Extract the key conditions from the CEX and write a targeted cover property:\n   cover property (state == S_X ##1 signal_y && !signal_z);\n   If that covers at shallow depth, you've found the local trigger pattern.\n\n6) Load in a simulator anyway — simulators can replay CEX waveforms for debugging even if reading the raw trace is hard."},
  {id:409,diff:"Debug",cat:"Debugging FPV",q:"You have a proof for a property. How do you gain confidence it's not a junk proof caused by bad assumptions?",a:"A proof is only as good as its environment. Validate systematically:\n\n1) Coverage of assumes: every assume should have a companion cover showing the constrained scenario is still reachable.\n\n2) Sanity covers: write covers for basic expected behaviours:\n   cover property (state == S_GRANT);  // design reaches grant state\n   cover property (tx_valid);           // transmission actually happens\n   All should be Covered.\n\n3) Mutation test the property set: inject a known bug into the RTL (flip an operator, change a constant). The property set should catch it. If the 'Proven' result doesn't change, your environment is likely too constrained.\n\n4) Spot-check the CEX on a related falsified property to confirm the tool is actually exploring real states.\n\n5) check_assumptions: run JasperGold's built-in consistency check.\n\n6) Peer review the assume set: have someone else read every assume and justify it against the spec."},
  {id:410,diff:"Debug",cat:"Debugging FPV",q:"What is the difference between 'Unreachable' and 'Uncovered' in JasperGold cover results?",a:"In JasperGold:\n\nCovered: a witness trace was found — the scenario is definitely reachable.\n\nUncovered: encompasses two distinct situations:\n  a) The tool formally PROVED the scenario is unreachable (equivalent to the Unreachability App result) — this is a strong result.\n  b) The BMC depth was insufficient to find a witness — the scenario might be reachable at greater depth (inconclusive).\n\nCritically: you cannot tell which case you have from 'Uncovered' alone without checking proof depth and engine status.\n\nActionable response:\n  - If proof depth is large and PDR completed: likely a genuine unreachability result. Investigate dead code.\n  - If BMC bounded only: increase depth or switch to Ht engine for a definitive unreachability proof.\n  - Always run 'report_property -name <cover>' to see which engine completed and at what depth."},
  // ===================== INTERVIEW SCENARIOS =====================
  {id:501,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",q:"'Walk me through a formal verification bug you found that simulation missed.'",a:"Structure your answer with: WHAT the design was, WHAT property you wrote, WHY simulation missed it, WHAT the CEX showed.\n\nExample framework:\n'I was verifying a credit-based flow control interface. I wrote a property asserting that the credit counter never goes below zero under any valid stimulus. Simulation had been running for weeks with directed and random tests. The formal tool found a CEX at depth 34 — a specific sequence where a credit return and a credit consume arrived on the same cycle, and the RTL's combinational update order meant the decrement was applied before the increment, momentarily going negative before recovering. The bug was in a 2-line always block that simulation hadn't hit because it required exactly the right concurrent stimulus pattern. FPV found it exhaustively in 4 minutes.'\n\nKey points to hit: exhaustiveness of FV vs finite sim, the specific root cause, the business impact (would have been a silicon bug)."},
  {id:502,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",q:"'How do you decide what to verify with FPV vs. simulation?'",a:"FPV is strongest for:\n- Control logic, FSMs, arbiters — finite, bounded state\n- Protocol properties (handshakes, ordering, flow control)\n- Safety invariants (never overflow, never deadlock)\n- Corner cases that require specific concurrent stimulus\n- Properties that simulation would need millions of cycles to hit\n\nSimulation is stronger for:\n- Wide datapaths (floating point, DSP) — state space too large for FPV\n- End-to-end system tests requiring full software stacks\n- Performance and timing characterisation\n- Scenarios requiring specific data content (image processing, encryption)\n- When the design is too large for tractable FPV even with abstraction\n\nIn practice: use FPV for control correctness, use simulation for data correctness and system integration. The two are complementary — FPV sign-off + simulation coverage closure gives much higher confidence than either alone."},
  {id:503,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",q:"'How do you scope an FPV effort on a block you've never seen before?'",a:"Week 1 process:\n1) Read the spec — identify: what are the interfaces? What are the protocols? What are the invariants explicitly stated?\n2) Run lint and Superlint — understand the design structure, find obvious issues.\n3) Write the simplest possible cover: cover property (1'b1); and get the tool running on the block. Proves the environment works.\n4) Identify the state-holding elements: FSMs, counters, FIFOs. These are your primary assertion targets.\n5) Characterise COI: which inputs drive which outputs? Use COI reports to find natural property partitions.\n6) Start with reset properties and basic interface protocol properties — these are always needed and are low-hanging fruit.\n7) Discuss with the RTL designer: what are they most worried about? What are the known hard cases?\n8) Build a property plan before writing SVA — agree on what Proven means for sign-off."},
  {id:504,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",q:"'The deadline is in 2 weeks and your FPV proof isn't converging. What do you do?'",a:"This is a prioritisation and communication question, not just a technical one.\n\nTechnical immediate actions:\n1) Switch to bounded proof: set_max_trace_length to reasonable depth, get a bounded result now.\n2) Apply maximum abstraction aggressively — blackbox everything non-critical, abstract all data.\n3) Split the proof: decompose into sub-properties that individually converge.\n4) Prioritise: which properties are highest risk? Prove those first, deprioritise lower-risk ones.\n\nProcess actions:\n5) Communicate immediately: tell your manager the proof is bounded, not complete. Document the bound depth.\n6) Quantify the risk: 'We've proven correctness up to depth N. Bugs beyond that depth require specific N-cycle sequences that simulation has never hit either.'\n7) Run simulation as a parallel track on the hard-to-prove paths.\n8) Never silently accept a bounded result as a full proof for sign-off — document it as bounded and get explicit sign-off acknowledgement."},
  {id:505,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",q:"'How do you convince RTL designers to write assertion-friendly code?'",a:"Don't make it about FV — make it about their interests:\n\n1) Show them a bug FV found: a concrete CEX that would have been a silicon bug is more persuasive than any process argument.\n\n2) Assertion-friendly code IS better code: FSMs with explicit state encoding, no latches, clear reset behaviour, explicit assumptions documented in comments — these all improve simulation debuggability too.\n\n3) Make it easy: provide templates and examples. If they see a 3-line assert that catches a whole class of bugs, adoption follows.\n\n4) Involve them early: ask 'what are you most worried about in this block?' and write properties for exactly that. When FV delivers value on their concerns, they become advocates.\n\n5) For management: frame it as risk reduction — FV-friendly RTL reduces tape-out risk. That language lands differently than 'it makes my job easier'.\n\n6) Never be adversarial about RTL style issues found by FV — bring them as 'FV flagged something, can we look at it together?' not as a gotcha."},
  {id:506,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",q:"'What does FPV sign-off mean to you? How do you know when you're done?'",a:"Sign-off is a risk statement, not a proof of perfection. A rigorous sign-off requires:\n\n1) All assertions proven or bounded with documented depth — no Falsified, no silent Unknowns.\n2) All cover properties Covered — no vacuous proofs hiding in the assert set.\n3) Vacuity check clean — every assert's antecedent has been demonstrated to fire.\n4) Assumption consistency verified — no contradictory assumes detected.\n5) COI analysis clean — every observable output of the block is in the COI of at least one property.\n6) Mutation score at agreed threshold (e.g. >=85%).\n7) Sign-off document: lists each property, its result, proof depth, and which spec requirement it covers.\n\nWhat sign-off does NOT mean: 'the design is bug-free.' It means: 'the design satisfies the properties we wrote, and we've verified those properties exercise the design meaningfully.' Property quality is the limit."},
  {id:507,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",q:"'Give me an example of an over-constrained FPV environment you debugged.'",a:"Structure: what the symptom was -> how you diagnosed it -> what the bad assume was -> what the fix was.\n\nExample framework:\n'We were verifying a 4-lane credit arbiter. All our assertions were proving quickly — suspiciously quickly. I ran cover properties for each grant signal and found that cover property (grant[2]) was Uncovered. Tracing back, we had an assume property ($onehot(req)) — one-hot request assumption — which excluded the case req==4'b0100 (only lane 2 requesting alone). The assume was supposed to model real traffic patterns but was actually written as $onehot instead of $onehot0, preventing any single-bit patterns from being explored fully due to an off-by-one in the encoding. Fixing to $onehot0 immediately made grant[2] coverable and exposed a real bug in the priority logic that had been masked.'\n\nKey structure: the symptom was easy proofs + uncovered covers, not an obvious error message."},
  {id:508,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",q:"'What is the hardest FPV environment you've had to set up and why?'",a:"Good answers demonstrate depth — this is not a trick question, they want to hear about genuine complexity.\n\nStrong topics to draw from:\n- Multi-clock designs where the interaction between domains created spurious CDC paths in the formal model\n- Designs with large memories that required abstract memory models without sacrificing correctness\n- Interfaces where the upstream environment was under-specified — had to reverse-engineer what valid stimulus looked like from RTL behaviour rather than a spec\n- Parameterised designs where properties had to scale correctly across multiple instantiation contexts\n- Designs with complex resets — multi-phase reset sequencing with different blocks coming out of reset at different times\n\nStructure your answer: what made it hard, what your approach was, what you tried that didn't work, what eventually worked. Interviewers at senior level want to see methodical thinking under uncertainty, not just a happy-path success story."},
  {id:509,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",q:"'How would you verify a round-robin arbiter using FPV?'",a:"Key properties for a round-robin arbiter:\n\n1) Mutual exclusion: assert property ($onehot0(grant));\n\n2) Grant only when requested: assert property (grant[i] |-> req[i]);  // per lane\n\n3) No starvation (bounded liveness): assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  req[i] |-> ##[1:N_LANES+1] grant[i]);\n  — in a fair round-robin, every requesting agent gets a grant within N+1 cycles.\n\n4) Priority rotation: cover that each lane gets priority — after lane i is granted, the next grant goes to lane i+1 (mod N).\n\n5) No grant when no request: assert property (!req |-> !grant);\n\n6) FSM reachability: cover each priority state.\n\nChallenge: the bounded liveness property (3) is the subtle one. If N is large, proof depth must exceed N. Set set_max_trace_length > N_LANES+2 at minimum."},
  {id:510,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",q:"'How do you handle a design where the RTL has uninitialized state (no hardware reset on some FFs)?'",a:"This is common in synthesis-optimised RTL where FFs with 'don't care' initial state are left without reset to save area.\n\nFPV approach:\n1) Identify the unreset FFs: Superlint/formal lint will flag them. Get the full list.\n2) For each: determine from the spec whether the initial value matters.\n  a) If truly don't-care (e.g. a data buffer FF): add an assume constraining the initial value to something representative, or leave as free variable and prove the property holds for ALL initial values.\n  b) If the initial value matters: this is an RTL bug — the FF needs a reset. Raise it.\n3) Do NOT blindly constrain all unreset FFs to 0 — that over-constrains and may hide bugs.\n4) Cover that the design behaves correctly from multiple initial conditions.\n5) Document every initial value assumption in the sign-off report with the justification."},
  {id:511,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",q:"'Explain your process for writing a new property set from scratch on an unfamiliar RTL block.'",a:"Structured process:\n\n1) Spec review: extract every MUST, NEVER, ALWAYS, WITHIN from the spec. These map directly to assert properties.\n\n2) Interface analysis: for every input/output port group, identify the protocol. Write handshake properties first — they are always needed.\n\n3) State machine extraction: read or extract the FSM from RTL. Write: state reachability covers for every state, transition covers for every arc, and illegal-state asserts.\n\n4) Counter/queue invariants: every counter needs a bounds assert. Every FIFO needs full/empty flag correctness.\n\n5) Data integrity: identify any path where data is stored and later retrieved. Write a symbolic scoreboard property.\n\n6) Sanity covers first: before running asserts, prove covers for basic scenarios. If covers pass, proceed.\n\n7) Incremental proof: add properties one group at a time. Don't add 50 properties and run — add 5, prove them, add 5 more. Easier to debug failures in small batches."},
  {id:512,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",q:"'What questions do you ask a designer before starting formal verification on their block?'",a:"Before touching the RTL:\n\n1) What are the 3 things you're most worried could go wrong in this block?\n2) What is the protocol on each interface — is there a spec doc or do I need to infer from RTL?\n3) Are there any known corner cases you haven't been able to test in simulation?\n4) What is the reset sequence — single reset, multi-phase, asynchronous?\n5) Are there any intentionally unreset flip-flops and which ones?\n6) What are the valid input ranges? Are there input combinations the upstream block would never produce?\n7) Has this block been modified from a previous tape-out version? If so, what changed?\n8) What coverage goals do you have from the simulation side — I'll make sure FV complements them.\n9) What's the sign-off criterion — what result do you need from FV to feel confident?\n\nThese questions demonstrate professionalism, identify where to focus effort, and surface assumptions before they become missing assumes."},
  // ===================== SIGN-OFF & METHODOLOGY =====================
  {id:601,diff:"Methodology_Adv",cat:"Sign-off & Methodology",q:"What goes in a formal verification sign-off document?",a:"A complete FPV sign-off document should contain:\n\n1) Scope: which RTL block(s), which revision, which interfaces were verified.\n2) Tool and version: JasperGold version, license, OS.\n3) Property inventory: every property by name, type (assert/cover/assume), status (Proven/Falsified/Bounded/Covered/Uncovered).\n4) Proof depth: for bounded results, the maximum depth explored.\n5) Engine configuration: which engines ran (Ht, Bmc, etc.).\n6) Assumption rationale: every assume justified against the spec or upstream guarantee.\n7) Exclusions: any properties excluded and why (dead code, out-of-scope, bounded-only).\n8) Vacuity results: confirmation that all asserts' antecedents fired.\n9) COI summary: which design signals are covered by at least one property.\n10) Mutation score: if run.\n11) Known limitations: what is NOT proven and why.\n12) Sign-off approvals: FV engineer, RTL designer, verification lead."},
  {id:602,diff:"Methodology_Adv",cat:"Sign-off & Methodology",q:"What is the difference between an FPV 'proof' and an FPV 'bounded result' for sign-off purposes?",a:"Proof (Proven): the property holds for ALL reachable states across ALL time — this is a mathematical guarantee. No depth limit. Obtained from PDR/IC3 or complete k-induction. This is the gold standard for sign-off.\n\nBounded result: the property holds for all stimulus up to depth N clock cycles. Bugs requiring more than N cycles to trigger are NOT ruled out. This is a partial result.\n\nFor sign-off, a bounded result must be accompanied by:\n1) Documentation of the bound depth\n2) Justification that the bound is sufficient (e.g. protocol guarantees completion within M cycles, and N >> M)\n3) Management acknowledgement of the residual risk\n4) Complementary simulation coverage for the bounded paths\n\nNever present a bounded result as equivalent to a full proof in a sign-off document."},
  {id:603,diff:"Methodology_Adv",cat:"Sign-off & Methodology",q:"How do you handle properties that cannot be proven but are low-risk? What is your escalation process?",a:"Properties that are Unknown/Inconclusive after maximum effort need a structured disposition:\n\nOptions (in order of preference):\n1) Decompose: split the property into sub-properties that individually converge. If sub-properties all prove, the original goal is satisfied compositionally.\n2) Abstract further: more aggressive blackboxing/abstraction. Accept narrower scope.\n3) Bounded sign-off: take the bounded result with documented depth, justify it's sufficient, get explicit management sign-off.\n4) Simulation augmentation: write targeted simulation tests that specifically exercise the patterns the FPV couldn't reach.\n5) Architectural review: if the property can't be proven because the design is too complex, that complexity is itself a risk signal — escalate to RTL designer.\n\nEscalation: never silently drop a property from the sign-off list. Every unproven property must appear in the sign-off document as an explicit exclusion with rationale and risk acceptance sign-off."},
  {id:604,diff:"Methodology_Adv",cat:"Sign-off & Methodology",q:"What is a formal verification plan and what should it contain before any RTL is written?",a:"An FV plan written pre-RTL aligns verification intent with design intent:\n\n1) Block scope: what module(s) will be verified, at what abstraction level.\n2) Interface specification: every port, its protocol, its constraints — becomes the assume set.\n3) Property categories: list what types of properties will be written (safety invariants, protocol properties, data integrity, FSM completeness).\n4) Abstraction strategy: which submodules will be blackboxed or modelled abstractly.\n5) Sign-off criteria: what constitutes a complete result (full proof, bounded depth, mutation score threshold).\n6) Schedule: when will the property set be ready, when will first proof runs happen, when is sign-off needed.\n7) Risks: what parts of the design are expected to be hard to prove and why.\n\nA pre-RTL plan catches interface misunderstandings early and prevents discovering late that the block was designed in a way that makes FPV intractable."},
  {id:605,diff:"Methodology_Adv",cat:"Sign-off & Methodology",q:"How do you version-control and regression-test an FPV property set?",a:"Treat the property set as first-class code:\n\n1) Source control: all .sv property files, TCL scripts, and constraint files in the same git repo as the RTL. Properties are reviewed alongside RTL changes in code review.\n\n2) CI regression: nightly FPV run on main branch. Fail the pipeline on any:\n   - New Falsified property (regression)\n   - Previously Covered property now Uncovered (regression)\n   - Proof depth increase beyond threshold (may indicate complexity growth)\n\n3) Baseline management: store the expected result (Proven/Bounded/Covered) per property in a results baseline file. CI diffs against baseline and flags deviations.\n\n4) Property tagging: each property is tagged with the spec requirement it covers. When the spec changes, you can identify which properties need updating.\n\n5) Mutation score tracking: track mutation score over time. A dropping score without new properties added means RTL diverged from properties."},
  {id:606,diff:"Methodology_Adv",cat:"Sign-off & Methodology",q:"How does assume-guarantee verification avoid circular reasoning?",a:"The risk: if A assumes G_B and B assumes G_A, you might prove A using G_B and prove B using G_A, but never actually check that G_A and G_B are simultaneously satisfiable — a circular proof.\n\nHow to avoid it:\n1) Check circular consistency: at least one component must be verified WITHOUT relying on a guarantee from a component that depends on it. Break the cycle.\n2) Use a base case: prove the guarantee holds initially (cycle 0) without any assumptions from the other component. Then prove it holds inductively.\n3) Well-foundedness: guarantees must refer to past behaviour only, not future. If G_A says 'A will produce X' and G_B says 'B will produce Y assuming A produces X', the dependency is one-directional — not circular.\n4) Formal check: some tools can detect circular assume-guarantee pairs automatically.\n5) Practice: in most industrial flows, the components have a natural producer-consumer relationship — the producer's guarantee does not depend on the consumer's guarantee, breaking circularity naturally."},
  {id:607,diff:"Methodology_Adv",cat:"Sign-off & Methodology",q:"What is the difference between black-box, white-box, and grey-box formal verification?",a:"Black-box: the module under verification is treated as having completely unconstrained outputs — maximum abstraction. Used when verifying a wrapper around a submodule. Risk: over-approximation causes spurious CEX.\n\nWhite-box: the full internal RTL is visible to and modelled by the formal tool. Maximum precision, maximum state space. Standard FPV mode.\n\nGrey-box: the module is replaced with an abstract model that captures SOME of its behaviour — typically its interface protocol and key invariants — without modelling the full internals. Simpler than real RTL but more constrained than black-box.\n\nGrey-box is the most useful for scalability: prove the submodule correct separately (white-box), extract its interface guarantees as a formal summary, and use that summary as the grey-box model in the parent's FPV environment."},
  {id:608,diff:"Methodology_Adv",cat:"Sign-off & Methodology",q:"What is compositional verification and when does it fail?",a:"Compositional verification proves a system correct by proving each component in isolation under assumptions about its environment, then composing the results.\n\nIt fails when:\n1) The component assumptions are not actually guaranteed by the environment.\n2) Circular dependencies exist in the assume-guarantee structure.\n3) The interaction between components creates emergent behaviour not captured by any individual component's properties — system-level bugs that only appear when combined.\n4) Timing interactions at component boundaries are abstracted away — correct individually but broken at the interface.\n\nMitigation: always follow compositional proofs with integration-level simulation or a (possibly bounded) system-level formal check that exercises component interactions directly."},
  // ===================== CDC FORMAL =====================
  {id:701,diff:"CDC",cat:"CDC Formal",q:"What is a clock domain crossing (CDC) and why is it hard to verify with standard FPV?",a:"A CDC occurs when a signal driven in one clock domain (clk_src) is sampled in another (clk_dst) without a proper synchroniser. The challenge for FPV:\n\n1) Standard SVA is single-clock or explicitly multi-clock — but the fundamental issue at a CDC is metastability, which is an analogue phenomenon SVA cannot model.\n2) Metastability means the receiving flop's output is non-deterministic for a bounded window — it may resolve to 0 or 1 regardless of the input value.\n3) Standard formal tools assume digital semantics (0 or 1 at every clock edge) and miss the non-deterministic resolution behaviour.\n4) Multi-clock SVA CAN check structural handshakes across domains but cannot verify that the synchroniser actually prevents metastability propagation.\n\nThat's why dedicated CDC formal apps (JasperGold CDC, Questa CDC, VC SpyGlass CDC) use specialised models that know how to reason about synchroniser behaviour."},
  {id:702,diff:"CDC",cat:"CDC Formal",q:"What does a CDC formal tool actually check?",a:"A formal CDC tool performs two distinct analyses:\n\n1) Structural CDC analysis: identifies every signal that crosses a clock domain boundary. Classifies crossings as:\n   - Synchronised: a recognised synchroniser topology is present (2-flop, 3-flop, MUX sync, handshake)\n   - Unsynchronised: a raw crossing with no synchroniser — potential bug\n   - False path: not a real CDC (constant, static, don't-care)\n\n2) Functional CDC analysis: uses formal methods to verify that synchronised crossings are CORRECTLY synchronised:\n   - For handshake protocols: proves req is stable before ack, data is stable during the handshake window\n   - For FIFOs: proves gray-code pointer encoding is correct (only one bit changes at a time)\n   - For pulse synchronisers: proves the pulse is wide enough to be captured\n\nFormal CDC does NOT prove metastability cannot occur — it proves the synchroniser topology is correct."},
  {id:703,diff:"CDC",cat:"CDC Formal",q:"What is a gray-code pointer and why is it used in async FIFOs? How does formal verify it?",a:"A gray code is a binary encoding where only one bit changes between consecutive values. In an async FIFO, the read and write pointers must be passed across the clock domain boundary to compute full/empty flags.\n\nWhy gray code: if multiple bits could change simultaneously (standard binary), the receiving domain might sample a partially-updated value — metastability hazard on multiple bits. With gray code, only one bit changes per count — at most one bit is metastable at any time.\n\nFormal verification:\n1) Assert the gray code property:\n   assert property (@(posedge clk) $countones(ptr ^ $past(ptr)) <= 1);\n   — at most one bit changes per cycle.\n2) Prove full/empty flags are correct relative to gray-coded pointers.\n3) Prove no overflow: write pointer never laps read pointer.\n4) Cover that full and empty are both reachable."},
  {id:704,diff:"CDC",cat:"CDC Formal",q:"What is a reconvergence CDC hazard and how does formal detect it?",a:"Reconvergence: two signals from the SAME source clock domain cross to the SAME destination domain via DIFFERENT synchronisers (or paths of different latency). They are logically related in the source domain but arrive at the destination with potentially different timing — creating a window where the destination sees an inconsistent combination.\n\nExample: a 2-bit state register where state[0] is synchronised via path A (2 cycles) and state[1] via path B (3 cycles). For one cycle in the destination domain, you see state[0] from the new value and state[1] from the old value — an illegal combination.\n\nFormal detection: CDC tools build a reconvergence analysis that identifies all signals sharing a common driver in the source domain and checks whether they can arrive at the destination in different cycles. If yes, flags as a reconvergence hazard requiring either: (a) a single multi-bit synchroniser, or (b) formal proof the illegal combination is never observable."},
  {id:705,diff:"CDC",cat:"CDC Formal",q:"What is a handshake synchroniser and how do you formally verify it?",a:"A handshake synchroniser safely transfers multi-bit data across a CDC using a req/ack handshake:\n\nProtocol:\n1) Source: asserts req, holds data stable\n2) Destination: samples req (via 2-flop sync), reads data, asserts ack\n3) Source: receives ack (via 2-flop sync), deasserts req\n4) Destination: deasserts ack\n\nFormal verification properties:\n1) Data stability during transfer:\n   assume property (@(posedge clk_src) req && !ack_synced |=> $stable(data));\n2) Req stability until ack:\n   assert property (@(posedge clk_src) req && !ack_synced |=> req);\n3) No new req before ack clears:\n   assert property (@(posedge clk_src) $fell(req) |-> !req ##[1:SYNC_LATENCY] !ack_synced);\n4) Cover full handshake:\n   cover property (req ##[1:MAX] ack ##[1:MAX] !req);"},
  {id:706,diff:"CDC",cat:"CDC Formal",q:"What is the difference between structural CDC analysis and functional CDC analysis?",a:"Structural CDC analysis (lint-style CDC tools):\n- Identifies clock domain boundaries by tracing clock sources through the netlist\n- Flags uncrossed signals (no synchroniser) as violations\n- Checks synchroniser topologies against a library of known-good patterns\n- Fast, scalable, works before functional simulation\n- Does NOT check whether the synchroniser is used correctly for the data being transferred\n\nFunctional CDC analysis (formal CDC tools):\n- Verifies handshake protocols are correctly implemented\n- Proves gray-code encodings have the one-bit-change property\n- Checks pulse synchronisers receive pulses wide enough to be captured\n- Verifies reconvergent signals are never used in illegal combinations\n- Slower, requires full RTL elaboration\n\nFor sign-off you need both: structural to ensure no raw crossings exist, functional to ensure the synchronisation logic is correct."},
  // ===================== LIVENESS & TEMPORAL LOGIC =====================
  {id:801,diff:"Liveness",cat:"Liveness & Temporal Logic",q:"What is LTL (Linear Temporal Logic) and how does it relate to SVA?",a:"LTL is a formal specification language for properties over linear infinite time sequences. Key operators:\n- G (globally): Gp — p holds at every time step forever\n- F (finally/eventually): Fp — p holds at some future time step. SVA has NO direct equivalent — true unbounded F requires infinite-path reasoning beyond standard FPV. The closest bounded approximation is ##[1:MAX_BOUND] p, where MAX_BOUND must be justified from the spec.\n\nSVA adds sequence-level operators (##, [*], [->]) that go beyond pure LTL, making it more expressive for hardware protocols."},
  {id:802,diff:"Liveness",cat:"Liveness & Temporal Logic",q:"What is a Buchi automaton and why does liveness verification need it?",a:"A Buchi automaton is a finite-state automaton that accepts infinite words (infinite sequences of states). Acceptance condition: the automaton accepts a path if at least one accepting state is visited infinitely often.\n\nWhy liveness needs it: safety properties can be checked by looking at finite prefixes — a violation is witnessed by a finite bad sequence. Liveness properties require reasoning over infinite paths — you need to prove there is no infinite path that avoids the good event.\n\nModel checking liveness: encode the negation of the liveness property as a Buchi automaton. Find if the product of the design transition system and the Buchi automaton has an accepting cycle reachable from the initial state. If yes — a liveness violation exists. This is why liveness model checking is harder: it requires cycle detection in the reachability graph, not just reachability."},
  {id:803,diff:"Liveness",cat:"Liveness & Temporal Logic",q:"What is a fairness constraint and write an SVA-style fairness assumption for an arbiter.",a:"A fairness constraint asserts that certain conditions hold infinitely often in any execution path considered by the model checker. Without fairness, liveness can be falsified by degenerate paths where one component is permanently starved — a path that exists in the formal model but not in reality.\n\nExample: proving request i is eventually granted. Without fairness, the tool finds a path where the arbiter permanently grants lane 0 and starves lane i — which violates the liveness property but violates the scheduling policy too.\n\nFairness assumption (SVA-style — bounded approximation):\n  assume property (@(posedge clk)\n    req[i] |-> ##[1:SCHED_BOUND] grant[i]);\n\nThis constrains the scheduler to grant within SCHED_BOUND cycles, making the bounded liveness property provable under reasonable scheduling assumptions.\n\nFor true GR(1) synthesis-style fairness, specialist tools like BoSy or dedicated LTL model checkers are needed beyond standard FPV."},
  {id:804,diff:"Liveness",cat:"Liveness & Temporal Logic",q:"What is GR(1) specification and why is it relevant to hardware verification?",a:"GR(1) (Generalized Reactivity of rank 1) is a fragment of LTL of the form:\n(GF a1 ^ GF a2 ^ ...) -> (GF g1 ^ GF g2 ^ ...)\n\nMeaning: IF the environment guarantees certain conditions happen infinitely often (fairness assumptions), THEN the system guarantees other conditions happen infinitely often (liveness guarantees).\n\nHardware relevance:\n- Arbiter correctness: IF every requester requests infinitely often THEN every requester is granted infinitely often\n- Bus protocol: IF the bus is eventually free THEN pending requests are eventually serviced\n- Flow control: IF credits are eventually returned THEN the transmitter is never permanently blocked\n\nGR(1) is attractive because it has polynomial-time synthesis algorithms — you can automatically synthesise a controller satisfying a GR(1) spec. For verification, you check whether an existing controller satisfies the GR(1) spec using specialised tools. Standard FPV tools handle GR(1) poorly — it requires dedicated algorithms."},
  {id:805,diff:"Liveness",cat:"Liveness & Temporal Logic",q:"How do you prove deadlock freedom using FPV?",a:"Deadlock: the system reaches a state where no progress is possible — every agent is waiting for a resource held by another.\n\nFPV approach:\n1) Define a 'progress' predicate: a boolean that is true whenever the system is doing useful work.\n\n2) Assert bounded progress:\n   assert property (@(posedge clk)\n     !progress |-> ##[1:TIMEOUT] progress);\n   — the system cannot be non-progressing for more than TIMEOUT cycles.\n\n3) OR assert no permanent stall:\n   assert property (@(posedge clk)\n     stall |-> ##[1:MAX_STALL] !stall);\n\n4) Cover all FSM states to ensure no state is a permanent sink.\n\n5) For formal deadlock freedom proofs: check that the reachable state space contains no cycles where all transitions are self-loops with no progress — this requires liveness model checking beyond standard safety FPV."},
  {id:806,diff:"Liveness",cat:"Liveness & Temporal Logic",q:"What is the difference between a safety property and a co-safety property?",a:"Safety property: 'nothing bad ever happens.' A safety violation is witnessed by a finite bad prefix — once you've seen the violation, you can stop. Standard FPV model checking is optimised for safety.\nFormal: p is safety if every infinite bad trace has a finite bad prefix.\n\nCo-safety property: 'something good eventually happens.' A co-safety satisfaction is witnessed by a finite good prefix.\nFormal: p is co-safety if every infinite good trace has a finite good prefix.\n\nCover properties in SVA are co-safety: you're looking for a finite witness trace demonstrating reachability.\n\nLiveness (strict sense): 'something good happens infinitely often' — requires infinite traces, not finitely witnessable in either direction. Full liveness needs Buchi automata and is beyond standard bounded FPV.\n\nPractical impact: FPV handles safety (assert) and co-safety (cover) natively. True liveness needs dedicated algorithms and tools."},
  // ===================== SPOT THE BUG II =====================
  {id:901,diff:"Bug2",cat:"Spot the Bug II",q:"What is wrong with this assume-guarantee composition?",code:"// Module A assumes B's output is valid\nassume property (@(posedge clk) b_valid |-> b_data != 0);\n// Module B assumes A's output is valid\nassume property (@(posedge clk) a_valid |-> a_data != 0);\n// Both in the same FPV environment",a:"This is a circular assume-guarantee pair — A's correctness relies on B's guarantee, and B's correctness relies on A's guarantee. Neither is proven independently.\n\nThe solver uses both assumes simultaneously to prove properties that would not hold if either component behaved incorrectly. Specifically:\n- The tool never checks that b_data != 0 is a real property of Module B\n- The tool never checks that a_data != 0 is a real property of Module A\n- Both are just asserted as axioms, creating a closed circle\n\nFix: break the circle. Prove Module B in isolation first (without the A assume), extract its guarantee (b_data != 0 when b_valid), then use that proven guarantee as an assume in Module A's verification environment. The dependency must be one-directional."},
  {id:902,diff:"Bug2",cat:"Spot the Bug II",q:"Find all bugs in this FSM property set.",code:"// IDLE=0, FETCH=1, EXEC=2, DONE=3\nassert property (@(posedge clk)\n  state == IDLE  |-> ##1 state == FETCH);\nassert property (@(posedge clk)\n  state == FETCH |-> ##1 state == EXEC);\nassert property (@(posedge clk)\n  state == EXEC  |-> ##1 state == DONE);\nassert property (@(posedge clk)\n  state == DONE  |-> ##1 state == IDLE);",a:"Three bugs:\n\n1) No disable iff: all four assertions fire during reset. If the reset state is IDLE, the first assertion immediately demands ##1 state==FETCH even while rst_n is low.\n\n2) Over-specification: mandates a rigid linear FSM with no branching. Real FSMs have conditional transitions — EXEC might go back to FETCH on a cache miss. These assertions will falsify valid RTL behaviour.\n\n3) Missing guard conditions: what causes FETCH->EXEC? The assertions say it must happen unconditionally every cycle, but there may be stall conditions (e.g. wait for memory). Need: state==FETCH && mem_ready |-> ##1 state==EXEC.\n\nFix: add disable iff, add guard conditions to each implication, and add cover properties for each state."},
  {id:903,diff:"Bug2",cat:"Spot the Bug II",q:"What is wrong with this data integrity property?",code:"logic [31:0] captured;\nalways_ff @(posedge clk)\n  if (wr_valid) captured <= wr_data;\n\nassert property (@(posedge clk)\n  rd_valid |-> rd_data == captured);",a:"Two bugs:\n\n1) captured is RTL ghost state in a synthesisable always_ff — it will be synthesised into the design if the property file is compiled with the RTL rather than in a separate bind module. Ghost state must be in a bind file or marked as formal-only, not synthesisable RTL.\n\n2) captured tracks the LAST write, not a write correlated to a specific read. If multiple writes occur between a write and its read, captured will have been overwritten. The property checks the last write's data against the read — only correct if there is a one-write-one-read ordering guarantee.\n\nFor a proper data integrity check: use a symbolic scoreboard (assume wr_data is a free variable at a specific address, assert rd_data returns that value). Or use an SVA local variable to capture at write time and check at the corresponding read."},
  {id:904,diff:"Bug2",cat:"Spot the Bug II",q:"What is wrong with this attempt to verify a memory?",code:"// Abstract memory model\nlogic [31:0] mem [0:255];\nalways_ff @(posedge clk)\n  if (wr_en) mem[wr_addr] <= wr_data;\n\nassert property (@(posedge clk)\n  rd_en |-> rd_data == mem[rd_addr]);",a:"Three issues:\n\n1) The abstract memory has 256x32 = 8192 state bits — enormous for FPV. A full memory model in an FPV environment is a classic scalability mistake; the proof will almost certainly not converge.\n\n2) The memory is not properly initialised. At cycle 0, mem contents are unknown. The assertion may fire on reset with uninitialised values.\n\n3) The correct FPV approach for memory data integrity is the symbolic address trick:\n  // Assume ONE symbolic address and data\n  assume property (@(posedge clk)\n    wr_en && wr_addr == ADDR_SYM |-> wr_data == DATA_SYM);\n  assert property (@(posedge clk)\n    rd_en && rd_addr == ADDR_SYM |-> rd_data == DATA_SYM);\nWhere ADDR_SYM and DATA_SYM are unconstrained free variables. This proves correctness for the symbolic address without modelling all 256 entries."},
  {id:905,diff:"Bug2",cat:"Spot the Bug II",q:"What is wrong with this multi-cycle path assertion?",code:"assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  start |-> ##1 step1 ##1 step2\n          ##1 step3 ##1 done);",a:"Two bugs:\n\n1) No disable iff: the property fires during reset. If start is high during reset (possible if it's a free variable), the assertion immediately demands a multi-cycle pipeline sequence through reset.\n\n2) The intermediate steps (step1, step2, step3) are required at EXACTLY cycles +1, +2, +3. But in a real pipeline with stall cycles, the pipeline pauses — the assertion demands progress every cycle regardless.\n\nFix: if stalls are possible, either use consecutive repetition with bounded range:\n  start |-> ##1 (step1 [->1]) ##1 (step2 [->1]) ##1 (step3 [->1]) ##1 done\nor restructure to check only the observable input/output relationship:\n  start |-> ##[LATENCY_MIN:LATENCY_MAX] done;"},
  {id:906,diff:"Bug2",cat:"Spot the Bug II",q:"What is wrong with this parameterised assertion?",code:"genvar i;\ngenerate\n  for (i=0; i<NUM_LANES; i++) begin\n    assert property (@(posedge clk)\n      req[i] |-> ##[1:8] grant[i]);\n  end\nendgenerate",a:"Two issues:\n\n1) No disable iff (!rst_n): during reset, if any req[i] is high (possible if req is a free variable), the property immediately demands grant[i] within 8 cycles from a reset state.\n\n2) The bound of 8 is hardcoded. If the arbiter is round-robin with NUM_LANES lanes, a requesting lane may have to wait up to NUM_LANES cycles for its turn. If NUM_LANES > 8, the assertion bound is too tight and will falsify correct behaviour.\n\nFix: set the bound to at least NUM_LANES+1 (or parameterise as MAX_WAIT), and add disable iff:\n  assert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)\n    req[i] |-> ##[1:NUM_LANES+1] grant[i]);"},
  {id:907,diff:"Bug2",cat:"Spot the Bug II",q:"What is wrong with this use of $past in a reset property?",code:"assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  $rose(rst_n) |-> $past(state, 1) == IDLE);",a:"$past(state, 1) at the cycle when $rose(rst_n) is true gives the value of state at the PREVIOUS cycle — which is the last cycle when rst_n was low (during reset).\n\nThe property checks: 'at the cycle reset deasserts, the state in the PREVIOUS cycle (during reset) was IDLE.' This may or may not be useful, but almost certainly NOT what was intended.\n\nTypical intent: 'after reset deasserts, the first post-reset state is IDLE.' Correct form:\nassert property (@(posedge clk)\n  $rose(rst_n) |=> state == IDLE);\n\nUsing |=> checks state at the NEXT cycle after $rose(rst_n) — the first clock edge after reset deasserts, when flops have propagated to their reset values.\n\n$past looks BACKWARDS; use |=> to check FORWARD."},
  {id:908,diff:"Bug2",cat:"Spot the Bug II",q:"What is wrong with this property intended to check a FIFO never loses data?",code:"assert property (@(posedge clk)\n  push_en && !full |=>\n    ##[1:DEPTH] (pop_en && pop_data == push_data));",a:"Three bugs:\n\n1) push_data is captured at push time but the sequence waits [1:DEPTH] cycles for pop. By then, push_data (an input) may have changed. The assertion checks push_data's CURRENT value at the pop cycle — not the value that was pushed. Fix: use a local variable:\n  (push_en && !full, data_cap = push_data) ##[1:DEPTH] (pop_en && pop_data == data_cap)\n\n2) The property does not specify WHICH pop is the corresponding one. If multiple pops happen, only the first matching pop satisfies the [1:DEPTH] window — other data might be silently dropped.\n\n3) No disable iff for reset — a push during reset creates an obligation that may not be satisfiable from the reset state."}
];
// ── COVERAGE APP (ids 1001–1010) ──────────────────────────────
ALL_QUESTIONS.push(
{id:1001,diff:"CovApp",cat:"Coverage App",
q:"What does the JasperGold Coverage App (FCA) prove, and how is it fundamentally different from simulation coverage?",
a:"The Coverage App formally proves whether each coverage target is REACHABLE under any possible input sequence.\n\nThree possible results:\n- Covered: formal witness found — there exists a valid input sequence that hits this target.\n- Unreachable: formally proven impossible. No input sequence, ever, can reach that code. Mathematical proof — not just 'we didn't test it.'\n- Undetermined: timed out or hit resource limits at the current proof depth.\n\nSimulation coverage gives you: 'these tests hit this line.'\nFormal coverage gives you: 'this line is provably reachable / provably dead.'\n\nThe Unreachable result is the key differentiator — it eliminates false coverage goals entirely, something simulation fundamentally cannot do. Simulation at 100% means every target was hit in some test. Formal closure means every reachable target is proven reachable and every dead one is proven dead."},

{id:1002,diff:"CovApp",cat:"Coverage App",
q:"What types of coverage targets does the JasperGold Coverage App analyse?",
a:"Line/statement coverage — which RTL lines are reachable.\nBranch coverage — both directions of every if/case branch.\nCondition coverage — each sub-expression in compound conditions.\nFSM state coverage — which states can be reached from reset.\nFSM transition coverage — which arcs of the state diagram can fire.\nToggle coverage — which signal bits can go 0->1 and 1->0.\nUser-defined cover properties — your SVA cover property() statements.\n\nFor each target: Covered (witness found) / Unreachable (proven impossible) / Undetermined (incomplete).\n\nThe Covered results come with witness traces you can replay in simulation as directed tests. The Unreachable results eliminate those targets from your simulation plan permanently."},

{id:1003,diff:"CovApp",cat:"Coverage App",
q:"What is 'formally closed coverage' and what are the conditions to claim it?",
a:"Formally closed coverage means every coverage target in scope has a definitive formal result — Covered or Unreachable.\n\nConditions to claim it:\n1. Zero Undetermined results — or all Undetermined targets explicitly bounded and accepted at documented proof depth.\n2. Every Unreachable target reviewed: intentional dead code (waived), RTL bug (fixed), or over-constrained environment (constraint loosened).\n3. The analysis ran with correct clock, reset, and environment constraints — not an over-constrained model making everything appear unreachable.\n4. Waivers signed off.\n\nFormal closure is stronger than simulation closure. 100% simulation coverage means every target was hit in some test — but the test may have used impossible stimulus. Formal closure means every unreachable result is a proof, not a gap."},

{id:1004,diff:"CovApp",cat:"Coverage App",
q:"How do formal coverage witnesses accelerate simulation coverage closure?",
a:"A coverage witness is the exact input sequence from reset that the solver found to hit a coverage target. It's the shortest proven path to a hard corner case.\n\nWorkflow:\n1. Run Coverage App. For every Covered target, JasperGold stores a witness trace.\n2. Export: report_witness -property <name> -format vcd -out witness.vcd\n   Batch: foreach p [get_property_list -include {status==covered}] { report_witness -property $p -format vcd -out witnesses/$p.vcd }\n3. Replay in simulation: convert VCD to UVM sequence or directed test. Run it — closes the coverage target immediately, mathematically guaranteed.\n\nFor Unreachable targets: stop writing tests entirely. They're dead code.\n\nThis eliminates the 'write 1000 random tests hoping to hit corner cases' anti-pattern. The formal tool hands you exact stimulus for every reachable corner case."},

{id:1005,diff:"CovApp",cat:"Coverage App",
q:"What is FSM coverage in the Coverage App and what are the most valuable findings?",
a:"The Coverage App auto-extracts FSMs from always_ff blocks and checks:\n- State reachability: can every encoded state be reached from reset?\n- Transition reachability: can every arc of the state diagram be taken?\n- Reset state: does the FSM always start in the documented reset state?\n\nMost valuable findings:\n1. Unreachable states: states that can never be entered. Often means: missing trigger condition, wrong encoding, or a feature spec'd but never implemented in the RTL entry path. Real RTL bug.\n2. Unreachable transitions: an arc exists in the RTL but the condition that fires it can never be true given inputs. Dead logic.\n3. Asymmetric reachability: you can reach state S from IDLE but can never return to IDLE from S. Potential deadlock.\n\nPair FSM coverage with explicit cover property assertions on each state to cross-validate the formal results with your property set."},

{id:1006,diff:"CovApp",cat:"Coverage App",
q:"How do you use formal coverage to eliminate simulation targets before running any simulation?",
a:"Run Coverage App before simulation, not after — this is the highest-ROI use.\n\n1. RTL drops. Run Coverage App immediately. No properties, no testbench needed.\n2. Get Unreachable list. These targets are provably dead. Remove them from your simulation coverage plan now.\n3. Update the verification plan: annotate each removed target with the formal proof as justification. No reviewer can argue with a formal proof.\n4. Remaining targets are all provably reachable. Simulation only needs to hit these.\n5. Export witnesses for Covered targets — replay them in simulation to close immediately.\n\nResult: your simulation plan is smaller (no dead targets), every target in it is achievable, and you have formal-generated stimulus for most. Coverage closure time drops significantly. You never write a test for dead code again."},

{id:1007,diff:"CovApp",cat:"Coverage App",
q:"What does an Unreachable coverage result mean for RTL quality and what do you do with each one?",
a:"An Unreachable result is a mathematical certificate that no input sequence can ever execute that code.\n\nWhat it means:\n1. Dead code — intentional or unintentional. May be a defensive default case (fine, waive it) or a feature the spec described but the RTL logic inadvertently blocks (RTL bug).\n2. Over-constrained environment — your assume set is too tight. The code would be reachable in reality, but your assumes prevent it. FV environment bug.\n\nDisposition process for every single Unreachable result:\n- Intentional dead code: waive with justification in sign-off document.\n- RTL bug: file bug, fix RTL, re-run.\n- Over-constrained: loosen the assume, re-run. If it becomes Covered, your original environment was wrong.\n\nNever silently batch-waive Unreachable results. Each one requires an explicit engineering decision."},

{id:1008,diff:"CovApp",cat:"Coverage App",
q:"What are the limitations of toggle coverage even when measured formally?",
a:"Toggle coverage tracks whether each signal bit can transition 0->1 and 1->0.\n\nIn formal: the Coverage App proves whether each toggle is achievable — Covered means the solver found a path that flips the bit; Unreachable means it's provably stuck.\n\nLimitations:\n1. Necessary but not sufficient. A bit that toggles in many wrong contexts passes toggle coverage. Toggling doesn't mean toggling correctly.\n2. No correlation between bits. Proving bit[0] can be 1 and bit[1] can be 1 independently doesn't prove they can be 1 simultaneously.\n3. No ordering. Toggle coverage is stateless — doesn't check that a toggle happens at the right time or in response to the right condition.\n4. Wide bus inflation. A 64-bit bus = 128 toggle targets. Formally proving all 128 tells you nothing about data path correctness.\n\nBest use: tells you which signals are live (not stuck at a constant). If a signal never toggles in either direction, it's dead logic. Combine with assertion coverage for meaningful behavioural checking."},

{id:1009,diff:"CovApp",cat:"Coverage App",
q:"Why do you need both formal coverage AND mutation coverage? What does each miss alone?",
a:"They answer completely different questions.\n\nFormal coverage (structural): 'Which parts of the RTL are reachable?' Says nothing about whether your verification catches bugs there.\n\nMutation coverage: 'Does my assertion set catch bugs?' Mutates the RTL (flip operator, offset constant, stuck bit) and checks whether any assertion falsifies the mutant. High score = properties are sensitive to RTL changes.\n\nWhat each misses alone:\n- 100% formal coverage + zero assertions = perfect coverage, zero bug-catching. Reachability proven, no properties to check correctness.\n- 100% mutation score + 20% formal coverage = strong assertions over 20% of the design. The other 80% unchecked.\n\nYou need both: formal coverage confirms every reachable state is being explored; mutation score confirms the property set catches bugs in those states. Sign-off requires demonstrating both dimensions."},

{id:1010,diff:"CovApp",cat:"Coverage App",
q:"Write the minimal JasperGold TCL script to run the Coverage App in batch mode and export results.",
a:"clear -all\nanalyze -sv09 -f filelist.f\nelaborate -top my_module\nclock clk\nreset -expression {!rst_n}\n\n# Run formal coverage\ncheck_coverage -type {line branch fsm toggle}\n\n# Report\nreport_coverage -summary\nreport_coverage -format html -out coverage_report.html\n\n# List unreachable targets\nset unreach [get_coverage_list -filter {status == unreachable}]\nforeach t $unreach { puts \"UNREACHABLE: $t\" }\n\n# Export witnesses for all covered targets\nfile mkdir witnesses\nforeach p [get_property_list -include {status == covered}] {\n  report_witness -property $p -format vcd \\\n    -out witnesses/${p}.vcd\n}\n\n# Run in batch: jg -batch -tcl run_cov.tcl -logfile cov.log"}
);

// ── ABSTRACTIONS & MODELLING (ids 1101–1110) ──────────────────
ALL_QUESTIONS.push(
{id:1101,diff:"Abstraction",cat:"Abstractions & Modelling",
q:"What is state space explosion and why does it kill FPV on large designs?",
a:"A design with N flip-flops has up to 2^N reachable states. A block with 100 FFs has more states than atoms in the observable universe. Formal tools prove properties by exploring this space — too large means timeout or memory exhaustion.\n\nExplosion contributors:\n- Wide data buses: a 32-bit bus contributes 2^32 values per cycle\n- Deep pipelines: state grows multiplicatively with depth\n- Large FIFOs: depth-256 width-32 FIFO has 8192 state bits — catastrophic\n- Interacting FSMs: independent state machines multiply the state space\n\nAbstraction is the engineering response: replace detailed logic with simpler models that preserve the properties being proven. Core principle: the abstract model must be a superset of real behaviours (soundness) — it may allow more behaviours (over-approximation) but must allow all real ones."},

{id:1102,diff:"Abstraction",cat:"Abstractions & Modelling",
q:"What is the standard 3-property FIFO abstraction and why is it sound?",
a:"A FIFO with depth D and width W has D*W state bits. The 3-property abstraction replaces the full model:\n\n1. Occupancy bounds:\nassert property (@(posedge clk) occupancy >= 0 && occupancy <= DEPTH);\n\n2. Flag correctness:\nassert property (@(posedge clk) full == (occupancy==DEPTH));\nassert property (@(posedge clk) empty == (occupancy==0));\n\n3. Data integrity (symbolic scoreboard):\n- Pick one symbolic address/position and one symbolic data value (free variables)\n- Track that symbolic data written at that position emerges in order at the output\n\nSoundness: by the substitution principle. Any component correctly interacting with the real FIFO will also correctly interact with any model satisfying these three observable contracts. The FIFO is then set_blackbox'd and its outputs constrained by these three assumes. State reduces from D*W bits to ~log2(D) bits (occupancy counter) + one symbolic pair."},

{id:1103,diff:"Abstraction",cat:"Abstractions & Modelling",
q:"What is counter abstraction and when is it valid?",
a:"Counter abstraction replaces a concrete N-bit counter with a free (unconstrained) variable plus boundary constraints.\n\nValid when: the property depends only on boundary behaviour (reaching max, reaching zero) — NOT on specific mid-range values.\n\nPattern:\n// Replace concrete counter with free variable\nlogic [W-1:0] credits_abs; // unconstrained\n// Add boundary constraints\nassume property (@(posedge clk) credits_abs <= MAX_CREDITS);\n// Prove boundary property\nassert property (@(posedge clk) !consume || credits_abs > 0);\n\nWhen NOT valid: if the property cares about specific mid-range values (e.g., 'exactly 3 cycles after req, grant fires'), abstraction loses precision.\n\nSoundness: the abstract model over-approximates — it allows the counter to jump anywhere within bounds between cycles. If a property is proven on the over-approximation, it holds on the concrete counter. If you get a CEX, verify it's not spurious by checking whether the counter jump is physically possible."},

{id:1104,diff:"Abstraction",cat:"Abstractions & Modelling",
q:"Describe the symbolic variable trick for memory verification. Write the bind file pattern.",
a:"A 256x32 memory has 8192 state bits — completely intractable. The trick: prove data integrity for ONE symbolic address and ONE symbolic data value. Because they're free variables, the proof holds for ALL addresses and ALL data simultaneously.\n\nBind file pattern:\nmodule mem_fv_props #(parameter AW=8, DW=32) (\n  input clk, rst_n,\n  input wr_en, [AW-1:0] wr_addr, [DW-1:0] wr_data,\n  input rd_en, [AW-1:0] rd_addr, output [DW-1:0] rd_data);\n\n  logic [AW-1:0] sym_addr; // free variable — solver picks any\n  logic [DW-1:0] sym_data; // free variable — solver picks any\n\n  logic written;\n  always_ff @(posedge clk or negedge rst_n)\n    if (!rst_n) written <= 0;\n    else if (wr_en && wr_addr==sym_addr && wr_data==sym_data)\n      written <= 1;\n\n  ap_integrity: assert property (\n    @(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)\n    written && rd_en && rd_addr==sym_addr\n    |-> rd_data == sym_data);\nendmodule\nbind mem_model mem_fv_props fv_i (.*);\n\nSolver treats sym_addr/sym_data as universally quantified — one proof covers all addresses and all data values."},

{id:1105,diff:"Abstraction",cat:"Abstractions & Modelling",
q:"What does set_blackbox do in JasperGold and what are the soundness implications?",
a:"set_blackbox -design {module_name} removes the module's entire internal logic. The module's output ports become FREE VARIABLES — unconstrained, can take any value at any time.\n\nSoundness:\n- Property PROVEN with blackbox: holds even when the module can output anything -> holds a fortiori for the real (more constrained) module. Safe.\n- CEX found with blackbox: may be spurious — the blackboxed module might have taken an output value the real module would never produce. Must verify.\n\nBest practice: after blackboxing, add assume properties constraining the module's outputs to its interface contract:\nset_blackbox -design {arbiter_sub}\nassume property (@(posedge clk) $onehot0(arb_grant)); // contract\nassume property (@(posedge clk) grant |-> $past(req)); // contract\n\nThis tightens the over-approximation and reduces spurious CEX."},

{id:1106,diff:"Abstraction",cat:"Abstractions & Modelling",
q:"What is `stopat` in JasperGold, how does it differ from set_blackbox, and when do you use it?",
a:"stopat <signal_path> cuts a specific signal — from that point forward it becomes a free variable. Signal-level abstraction vs. set_blackbox's module-level abstraction.\n\nKey difference:\n- set_blackbox: removes entire module, all outputs free.\n- stopat: cuts ONE signal anywhere in hierarchy, regardless of module boundaries. More surgical.\n\nWhen to use stopat:\n1. Only one output of a submodule is causing complexity — blackboxing the whole module is too coarse.\n2. Formal fault injection: stopat on a state register output (e.g., FSM state_o) injects any arbitrary value. Prove security properties hold under any corrupted state. This is how OpenTitan verifies prim_count and prim_double_lfsr security assertions — stopat on state registers, then prove fault-detection properties activate under any corrupted state.\n3. Cutting combinational feedback loops causing convergence problems.\n\nJG command: stopat dut.datapath.complex_unit.result\n\nSoundness: same as cutpoints — over-approximation. Proofs hold; CEX may be spurious."},

{id:1107,diff:"Abstraction",cat:"Abstractions & Modelling",
q:"What is a ghost (auxiliary) variable, where MUST it live, and why?",
a:"A ghost variable is verification-only logic tracking design state to enable richer assertions — never synthesised, never in the real design.\n\nWhere it MUST live: in a separate bind file — NEVER inside the RTL module being verified.\n\nWhy: putting always_ff ghost logic inside the RTL module causes it to synthesise — you've permanently added state to the real design. Hard bug.\n\nCorrect pattern:\n// In arbiter_fv.sv (bind file ONLY):\nmodule arbiter_fv (input clk, rst_n, req, ack);\n  // Ghost: tracks how many cycles req has been waiting\n  logic [7:0] req_age;\n  always_ff @(posedge clk or negedge rst_n)\n    if (!rst_n || !req) req_age <= 0;\n    else req_age <= req_age + 1;\n\n  // Bounded latency assertion using ghost\n  ap_latency: assert property (\n    @(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)\n    req_age >= MAX_WAIT |-> ack);\nendmodule\nbind arbiter arbiter_fv fv_i (.*);\n\nCompile only under +define+FPV=1. The DUT sees no changes. Bind injects non-intrusively."},

{id:1108,diff:"Abstraction",cat:"Abstractions & Modelling",
q:"What is set_case_analysis in JasperGold and how does it differ from an assume property?",
a:"set_case_analysis <value> <signal_path> forces a signal to a constant value at ELABORATION TIME — it's compile-time constant propagation. The solver simplifies the logic netlist, collapsing all logic in the COI that depends on this signal.\n\nset_case_analysis 0 {dut.dft_mode}  // DFT logic collapses out of the model\nset_case_analysis 1 {dut.func_en}   // Functional path always active\n\nDifference from assume property:\n- set_case_analysis: acts at elaboration time — actually simplifies the circuit. Smaller model, faster proof.\n- assume property (@(posedge clk) !dft_mode): runtime constraint. The DFT logic is still in the model; the solver just never explores paths where dft_mode=1. Less efficient.\n\nUse set_case_analysis for signals that are truly constant in the verification context (DFT mode, configuration bits, clock gate enables). Use assume for signals that are almost always a certain value but can change (e.g., a feature enable that's usually 1 but you want to constrain for this proof)."},

{id:1109,diff:"Abstraction",cat:"Abstractions & Modelling",
q:"What is reset abstraction and when does it help convergence?",
a:"Reset abstraction allows the solver to start from non-zero initial state values — instead of forcing the proof to always begin from the fixed post-reset state.\n\nWhy it helps:\n1. FIFO pointer wrap-around bugs: pointers reset to 0, interesting bugs happen near DEPTH. Reset abstraction lets the solver start with pointers near DEPTH and find wrap bugs at proof depth=2 instead of depth=DEPTH.\n2. Slow ramp-up designs: designs that need many cycles post-reset to reach interesting states. Reset abstraction jumps directly to mid-operation states.\n3. Counter overflow: start near MAX rather than from 0 — finds overflow bugs at depth=1.\n\nIn JasperGold: constrain initial values in the bind file rather than forcing fixed reset values:\n// Allow write pointer to start anywhere within valid range\nassume property (@(posedge clk) $past(cyc_cnt,1)==0 |-> wr_ptr inside {[0:DEPTH-1]});\n\nCaveat: a CEX from non-zero initial state may not be reachable from real reset. Validate whether the initial state requires a long sequence to reach from reset before filing as a real bug."},

{id:1110,diff:"Abstraction",cat:"Abstractions & Modelling",
q:"What makes an FPV environment model good vs. dangerous?",
a:"The environment model is the set of assumes constraining the DUT's inputs to valid stimulus space.\n\nGood environment model:\n- Tight enough: excludes physically impossible inputs (push when full, address out of range).\n- Loose enough: includes ALL valid input sequences the real system can produce. Over-constraining hides real bugs.\n- Every assume cites a spec clause as justification.\n- Companion cover properties verify every assume is satisfiable. If a cover is Uncovered, an assume is too tight.\n- Correct reset modelling: inputs behave correctly during and after reset.\n\nDangerous patterns:\n- Copied assumes from a previous project: massively over-constrains the new design, produces vacuous proofs.\n- Assume that mirrors the assert: assume (A |-> B) while trying to prove (A |-> B). You've assumed the conclusion. Instant vacuous proof.\n- Missing assumes: solver explores physically impossible inputs, generates false CEX.\n\nThe triangle of trust: write assumes -> write covers verifying assumes are satisfiable -> write asserts. If a cover is Uncovered, an assume is too tight. If a CEX looks wrong, an assume is missing."}
);

// ── SVA INTERNALS (ids 1201–1207) ─────────────────────────────
ALL_QUESTIONS.push(
{id:1201,diff:"SVA_Int",cat:"SVA Internals",
q:"What is the difference between antecedent vacuity and consequent vacuity in SVA?",
a:"Two distinct vacuity types, often conflated:\n\nAntecedent vacuity (common): the antecedent of an implication NEVER fires. Property p |-> q proves because p is never true — nothing is ever checked.\nExample: assert property (state==S_GRANT |-> grant_valid);\nIf state never reaches S_GRANT, this proves vacuously.\nDetection: run companion cover property (state==S_GRANT). If Uncovered, antecedent never fires. JasperGold check_vacuity catches this.\n\nConsequent vacuity (harder to catch): the consequent q is always true regardless of the antecedent — it's a tautology.\nExample: assert property (req |-> (a || !a));\nConsequent (a||!a) is always true. Property proves trivially even if req fires constantly.\nDetection: requires mutation testing or manual review. JasperGold check_vacuity primarily catches antecedent vacuity — consequent vacuity requires mutation testing (flip an operator in the consequent; if the assertion still passes, the consequent may be a tautology)."},

{id:1202,diff:"SVA_Int",cat:"SVA Internals",
q:"What are the exact semantics of `disable iff` — synchronous or asynchronous — and why does it matter?",
a:"disable iff implements ASYNCHRONOUS disabling — property evaluation is abandoned immediately when the disable condition becomes true, not at the next clock edge.\n\n- The disable condition is sampled continuously. If rst_n goes low MID-SEQUENCE, in-flight evaluations are abandoned at that point.\n- No failure is reported for the abandoned incomplete sequence.\n\nWhy it matters:\nFor asynchronous reset designs — if reset deasserts between clock edges, disable iff correctly abandons evaluation immediately. A synchronous model (using |-> in the clock domain) only checks reset at clock edges and CAN miss a brief async reset pulse.\n\nCorrect for async reset design:\nassert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)\n  req |-> ##[1:8] ack);\n\nSynchronous-only model (less correct for async reset):\nassert property (@(posedge clk) (!rst_n) |-> ...);\n// Only checks reset at posedge clk — misses sub-cycle async behaviour\n\nFor synchronous reset designs: both forms give equivalent results. For async reset designs: always use disable iff."},

{id:1203,diff:"SVA_Int",cat:"SVA Internals",
q:"What are the scoping rules for local variables in SVA sequences?",
a:"Local variables capture values mid-sequence and carry them forward. Key rules:\n\n1. Scoped to the declaring sequence — cannot be referenced outside it.\n2. Comma operator assigns on firing: (condition, var = expr) — assignment happens when the condition is satisfied at that sequence step.\n3. Antecedent->consequent transfer: local variables declared in the antecedent CAN be used in the consequent. Main use case: capture data at write time, verify at read time.\n4. Repetitions [*N]: the variable is NOT shared across repetitions — each iteration gets its own instance. Use external ghost logic if you need to accumulate across repetitions.\n\nExample:\nproperty data_integrity;\n  logic [31:0] cap;\n  @(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)\n  (wr_en, cap = wr_data) |-> ##[1:16] (rd_valid && rd_data == cap);\nendproperty\n\nThis captures wr_data at write time, then checks rd_data matches within 16 cycles."},

{id:1204,diff:"SVA_Int",cat:"SVA Internals",
q:"What does `bind` do in SystemVerilog, what are the advantages for FPV, and what are its hard limits?",
a:"bind <target_module> <checker_module> <instance_name> (<connections>);\n\nbind injects a checker module into target_module's scope non-intrusively. The checker sees all DUT internal signals. The RTL source is unchanged.\n\nAdvantages:\n- Non-intrusive: RTL unchanged, zero synthesis impact.\n- Full internal visibility: checker can reference any internal signal, not just ports.\n- Reusable: same bind file applies to every instance of the module.\n- Excludable: compile only under +define+FPV=1 — synthesis never sees it.\n\nHard limits:\n- Read-only: checker can READ internal DUT signals but CANNOT drive them back into the DUT.\n- No new I/O: you cannot add visible ports to the target module via bind.\n- Parameterised targets: need careful parameter matching in the bind statement."},

{id:1205,diff:"SVA_Int",cat:"SVA Internals",
q:"What is the most common SVA bug from confusing |-> and |=>?",
a:"The most common: using |-> (same-cycle) instead of |=> (next-cycle) for a registered output.\n\n|-> overlapping: antecedent true at cycle T -> consequent must be true at SAME cycle T.\n|=> non-overlapping: antecedent true at cycle T -> consequent must be true at cycle T+1.\n|=> is exactly equivalent to: |-> ##1\n\nBuggy (registered output):\nassert property (@(posedge clk) wr_en |-> reg_updated);\n// reg_updated is a flip-flop — it appears ONE cycle AFTER wr_en\n// Same-cycle check is always false -> assertion constantly fails or is trivially vacuous\n\nCorrect:\nassert property (@(posedge clk) wr_en |=> reg_updated);\n\nAnother common confusion:\nassert property (@(posedge clk) count==MAX |-> count==0);\n// Same cycle: count can't be MAX and 0 simultaneously\nassert property (@(posedge clk) count==MAX |=> count==0);\n// Next cycle: checks counter wraps after MAX — correct\n\nRule: combinational relationship -> use |->; registered output -> use |=>."},

{id:1206,diff:"SVA_Int",cat:"SVA Internals",
q:"What do $rose, $fell, $stable, $changed actually sample, and what are the critical edge cases to know?",
a:"All four compare current sampled value against PREVIOUS SAMPLED value (one clock tick ago):\n\n$rose(x): LSB was 0 last cycle, is 1 this cycle. Equivalent to: !$past(x) && x\n$fell(x): LSB was 1 last cycle, is 0 this cycle. Equivalent to: $past(x) && !x\n$stable(x): same value as last cycle. Equivalent to: x == $past(x,1)\n$changed(x): different value than last cycle. Equivalent to: !$stable(x)\n\nCritical edge cases:\n1. Undefined at time 0: no 'previous' value exists. Defaults: $stable->1, $rose->0, $fell->0, $changed->0. $stable(data) silently passes at reset even if data is garbage. ALWAYS use disable iff(!rst_n).\n\n2. $rose/$fell only check the LSB for multi-bit expressions. For multi-bit transition detection use $changed.\n\n3. Stability gotcha: $stable(data) is true on the very first cycle even if data was garbage before — it just needs to not change THIS cycle vs. last. Guard explicitly:\n  valid && !$past(valid) |=> $stable(data) // stability from second valid cycle\n\n4. $past(x, N) returns 0 for time steps before N cycles have elapsed — causes false passes at startup without disable iff."},

{id:1207,diff:"SVA_Int",cat:"SVA Internals",
q:"What are strong vs. weak SVA operators (IEEE 1800-2012) and when do they matter in formal?",
a:"Weak operators (default): if a sequence doesn't complete by end of proof horizon, the property PASSES. Incomplete = vacuous pass.\n\nStrong operators (s_ prefix): if sequence doesn't complete by end of proof horizon, property FAILS. Incomplete = violation.\n\nKey strong operators:\n- s_eventually(p): fails if p never becomes true within proof bound\n- s_nexttime(p): fails at last evaluated time step if p not seen\n- strong(seq): makes any sequence fail-if-incomplete\n\nWhen they matter in formal:\n- Weak semantics + bounded proof: a liveness property ##[1:$] ack may 'pass' if the solver can't find a long enough CEX within the depth. Property passes vacuously for short paths that don't resolve.\n- Strong semantics: s_eventually ack fails if the solver finds ANY finite path where ack never fires — closer to true liveness checking.\n\nPractical reality: most industrial FPV uses explicit bounded ranges (##[1:MAX_CYCLES]) rather than s_eventually because strong operator proof behaviour varies by tool version and proof depth. Explicit bounds are more predictable and debuggable."}
);

// ── METHODOLOGY: HYBRID FLOWS (ids 1301–1308) ─────────────────
ALL_QUESTIONS.push(
{id:1301,diff:"Hybrid",cat:"Methodology",
q:"What is the two-phase FPV methodology and why is it structured this way?",
a:"Phase 1 — Structural (before writing any SVA property):\n- Superlint App: latches, reset-incomplete FFs, dead states, combo loops, X-propagation\n- Coverage App: identify dead code before investing in functional properties\n- Connectivity App: verify expected paths exist / unwanted paths don't\n- CDC App: structural clock domain violations\nGoal: RTL is structurally clean. Typically takes days.\n\nPhase 2 — Functional FPV:\n- Write and prove SVA properties, scoped using Phase 1 results\nGoal: prove the design does what the spec says.\n\nWhy structured this way:\n1. Phase 1 catches real bugs immediately with high ROI — no property writing required.\n2. Structural bugs corrupt functional proofs. A latch or reset issue causes spurious CEX in functional properties. Fix structure first.\n3. Dead code from Phase 1 eliminates a portion of functional scope — smaller Phase 2.\n4. Phase 1 runs can start the moment RTL drops, while property writing happens in parallel."},

{id:1302,diff:"Hybrid",cat:"Methodology",
q:"What are the top reasons FPV efforts fail or get abandoned on real projects?",
a:"1. Scope too large from day one: trying to verify a 100K-line SoC block instead of individual modules. State space explodes immediately. Fix: always start with block-level FPV.\n\n2. No sign-off criteria defined upfront: team runs FPV with no agreed exit conditions. Proof runs indefinitely. Fix: agree on proof targets, depth, mutation score before writing the first property.\n\n3. Properties written without design understanding: trivially vacuous or constantly falsifying correct RTL. Fix: day-1 pairing between FV engineer and RTL designer is mandatory.\n\n4. Non-convergence treated as 'FPV doesn't work here': first run doesn't converge so the team quits. Convergence requires iteration — abstraction, blackboxing, case-splitting. Fix: treat non-convergence as an engineering problem.\n\n5. Over-constrained environment caught late: everything proves fast. Looks great. Sign-off review: half the covers are Uncovered. Months of vacuous proofs. Fix: run companion covers alongside every assert from day 1.\n\n6. Schedule: FPV added post-RTL-freeze as an afterthought. No time for iteration. Fix: FPV planning at spec phase.\n\n7. Resource: formal is compute-heavy. Shared underpowered machines. Fix: dedicated compute and licences upfront."},

{id:1303,diff:"Hybrid",cat:"Methodology",
q:"How do you use formal witnesses as simulation seeds?",
a:"A formal witness is the exact input sequence from reset that the solver found to prove a cover property. It's the shortest proven path to a corner case.\n\nWorkflow:\n1. Run FPV with cover properties or run Coverage App.\n2. Export witness: report_witness -property <name> -format vcd -out witness.vcd\n   Batch: foreach p [get_property_list -include {status==covered}] { report_witness -property $p -format vcd -out witnesses/$p.vcd }\n3. Convert VCD to UVM sequence or $readmemh stimulus.\n4. Run in simulation — closes the coverage target immediately, mathematically guaranteed.\n\nFor a 12-cycle sequence that only occurs at FIFO wrap with simultaneous push/pop, the witness is the only practical way to get there reliably.\n\nAlso useful for bug reporting: when FPV finds a CEX, export as simulation replay to demonstrate the bug in a waveform viewer the RTL team is comfortable with."},

{id:1304,diff:"Hybrid",cat:"Methodology",
q:"How do you port SVA assertions between formal and simulation flows?",
a:"Assertions written for FPV should be reused in simulation. Key differences to manage:\n\n1. disable iff: works correctly in both flows. Leave as-is.\n\n2. Assume properties: in FPV, assumes constrain input space. In simulation, assumes are treated as assertions — a testbench violating an assume fires as a failure. Useful (catches testbench bugs). To silence in sim: `ifndef FORMAL assume property (...); `endif\n\n3. Unbounded sequences (##[0:$]): valid in formal. In simulation can hang if condition never fires. Replace with explicit bounds: ##[0:MAX_LATENCY].\n\n4. Ghost variables in bind files: compile in both flows — the bind file is included in simulation too and acts as a runtime monitor.\n\n5. OpenTitan macro pattern (standard industry approach):\n`ASSERT(name, prop, clk, rst)     -> assert property in both flows\n`ASSUME_FPV(name, prop, clk, rst) -> assume in FPV, assert in simulation\n`COVER(name, prop, clk, rst)      -> cover property in both flows\n\nThis maximises reuse and ensures testbench compliance with formal constraints."},

{id:1305,diff:"Hybrid",cat:"Methodology",
q:"What is unreachable state elimination and why is it the highest-ROI use of formal?",
a:"Classic simulation problem: millions of cycles but can't reach 100% coverage. Remaining targets are either (a) reachable but needing specific stimulus or (b) genuinely dead code. Without formal, you can't tell which — you write tests for (b) forever.\n\nFormal solution — zero property writing required:\n1. Run Coverage App when RTL drops.\n2. Every Unreachable result: remove from simulation plan. The formal proof is the justification.\n3. Every Covered result: export witness, replay in simulation — immediate closure.\n4. Remaining targets: all provably reachable. Focus ALL simulation effort here.\n\nWhy highest ROI: requires no property writing. Just run the Coverage App. Output: a cleaned simulation plan with no dead targets and formal-generated stimulus for the reachable ones. You stop wasting compute on dead code permanently."},

{id:1306,diff:"Hybrid",cat:"Methodology",
q:"What is waveform-driven assume generation and what are its risks?",
a:"Mines existing simulation waveforms to auto-draft assume properties — rather than writing them from scratch against the spec.\n\nWorkflow:\n1. Run existing simulation (UVM, directed, random), capture VCD/FSDB.\n2. Mine for patterns: signals always correlated, constraints always satisfied. (e.g., push_en && full never co-occurred in 10M cycles)\n3. Translate to assume properties: assume property (full |-> !push_en);\n4. Validate: run companion cover properties to verify assumes are satisfiable.\n\nRisks:\n- Simulation may not have explored all valid input patterns. Mined assumes may be too tight, hiding real bugs.\n- Simulation correlations may be testbench artefacts, not architectural constraints.\n- Mined assumes that mirror your asserts prove nothing — you've assumed the conclusion.\n\nAlways validate mined assumes with companion covers before using in sign-off runs. Treat as a draft, not a final answer."},

{id:1307,diff:"Hybrid",cat:"Methodology",
q:"What is assume-guarantee reasoning and how is it applied in practice?",
a:"Assume-guarantee reasoning decomposes a large verification problem by specifying contracts at module boundaries.\n\nPrinciple:\n- Module A's spec becomes the assume set for Module B's proof (A guarantees its interface; B can assume it).\n- Module B's spec becomes the assume set for Module A's proof.\n- Each module proved independently using the other's contract.\n\nPractical workflow:\n1. Write interface contracts for each module — what it guarantees on outputs given valid inputs.\n2. Prove each contract formally.\n3. In adjacent modules' FPV environments, instantiate proven contracts as assume properties.\n4. Prove adjacent modules' properties with these assumes — no need to re-verify submodules.\n\nBenefit: avoids state-space explosion of full-system verification. Each module's proof is bounded to its own state space plus a lightweight contract model of its neighbours.\n\nChallenge: incomplete or wrong contracts mean the composed system can have bugs even though each piece proved independently. Contract completeness is the hard part — companion covers and the Coverage App help catch gaps."},

{id:1308,diff:"Hybrid",cat:"Methodology",
q:"What is the Cone of Influence (COI) in formal and how do you use it to guide abstraction?",
a:"The COI of a property is the set of all signals and logic that can affect the property's outcome — the transitive fan-in through both combinational and sequential logic.\n\nWhy it matters: JasperGold only explores the state space of signals in the COI. Logic outside the COI is irrelevant to this proof and is ignored. Large COI = many state bits in the proof = high complexity = potential non-convergence.\n\nUsing COI to guide abstraction:\n1. Analyse COI: report_coi -property {my_assert}\n2. Find the largest contributors: which submodules drive the most COI signals?\n3. Blackbox the largest irrelevant contributors: if a complex memory controller appears in the COI but only its outputs matter (not its internals), blackbox it.\n4. Verify COI shrinks: re-run report_coi after blackboxing.\n5. Check for unexpected signals: a signal you didn't expect in the COI means either a missing assume constraint (that would exclude it) or a property that's broader than intended.\n\nTCL: set coi [get_coi_signals -property {my_prop}]; puts [llength $coi]"}
);

// ── INTERVIEW SCENARIOS: Design an FPV Environment (ids 1401–1410) ──
ALL_QUESTIONS.push(

{id:1401,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",
q:"Design a complete FPV environment for a 4-lane AXI4 interconnect. Walk through every decision you'd make from RTL handoff to sign-off.",
a:`Walk through in this order:

1. UNDERSTAND THE SPEC FIRST
Before writing a line of SVA: read the AMBA AXI4 spec. Identify which rules are mandatory (no response without request), which are advisory (latency SLOs), and which are your design-specific additions (ordering guarantees, error handling). This scoping call saves weeks.

2. PHASE 1 — STRUCTURAL
Run Superlint immediately on RTL drop: catch latches, reset-incomplete FFs, dead states. Run Connectivity App to verify all 4 lanes connect correctly to the crossbar, no crossed wires, no missing paths.

3. ENVIRONMENT MODEL
- Clock: separate clock per channel if CDC exists; otherwise single clock
- Reset: AXI requires ARESETn held low for ≥1 cycle — model correctly with async reset
- Master model: assume AWVALID/WVALID/ARVALID follow AXI handshake rules (valid doesn't deassert while waiting for ready)
- Slave model: assume BVALID/RVALID issued only after corresponding request

4. CORE PROPERTIES
- Handshake stability: valid && !ready |=> $stable(valid) and $stable(chan_signals)
- Response ordering: BRESP/RRESP must correspond to the correct AWID/ARID
- No spurious response: BVALID |-> prior AWVALID with matching AWID
- ID uniqueness: no two outstanding transactions share the same ID per lane
- Lane isolation: traffic on lane[i] never corrupts lane[j] state

5. GHOST VARIABLES
AXI ordering requires tracking in-flight transaction IDs — can't do it without a ghost scoreboard in a bind file. Track: write address issued → write data → write response per AWID.

6. COVERAGE
Cover all 4 lanes active simultaneously. Cover back-to-back transactions (no idle gap). Cover max outstanding transactions. Cover OKAY, SLVERR, DECERR response codes.

7. ABSTRACTION
If the interconnect includes buffering/FIFOs, abstract them with the 3-property pattern. Blackbox any QoS arbitration logic not under test — it's irrelevant to the channel correctness properties.

8. SIGN-OFF
Proven: all handshake, ordering, lane isolation properties. Covered: all cover properties reachable. Vacuity: clean. Mutation score: ≥85%. Document the bounded depth (ordering properties may need depth=20+).`},

{id:1402,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",
q:"How would you set up FPV for a credit-based flow control block with 8 virtual channels, each with independent credit counters?",
a:`This is a common senior-level scenario. Key challenges: 8 independent counters, inter-channel isolation, no overflow/underflow.

ENVIRONMENT SETUP
- One clock, synchronous reset to known state (all counters = MAX_CREDITS)
- Constraints: credit_return[i] only asserts if prior credit_consume[i] asserted — you can't return credits you never issued. Model this per-channel with a ghost occupancy counter.

CORE PROPERTIES (for each channel i, use generate loop):
genvar i;
generate for (i=0; i<8; i++) begin : gen_ch
  // No consume when empty
  ap_no_underflow: assert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)
    credits[i] == 0 |-> !consume[i]);
  // Counter stays in bounds
  ap_bounds: assert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)
    credits[i] <= MAX_CREDITS);
  // Return only after consume (ghost enforced via assume)
  ap_no_spurious_return: assert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)
    cum_returns[i] <= cum_consumes[i]);
end endgenerate

ISOLATION PROPERTY — critical and often missed:
// Activity on channel j must not affect channel i's counter
// Proven implicitly if each counter's COI excludes other channels —
// verify this with report_coi and inspect for cross-channel signals

GHOST VARIABLES
Cumulative consume/return counters per channel to track the spurious-return constraint. Must be in bind file.

ABSTRACTION
If upstream logic that issues consumes is complex: blackbox it, assume consume[i] can fire any time credits[i] > 0. This constrains the over-approximation correctly.

CONVERGENCE
8 counters × counter width bits = significant state. Abstract with counter abstraction (free variable + bounds) if proof doesn't converge. The boundary properties are what matter, not mid-range values.`},

{id:1403,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",
q:"You're handed a FIFO that has been in silicon twice before and 'always worked.' How do you approach FPV on it?",
a:`'Always worked in simulation' is not a verification closure argument. Here's the approach:

1. TREAT IT AS UNVERIFIED
The fact that it passed simulation before means the common paths are probably fine. The interesting question is: what corner cases did simulation never explore? FIFO wrap-around with simultaneous push/pop. Full→empty in one cycle (if flush logic exists). Pointer aliasing at exact depth boundary.

2. RUN COVERAGE APP FIRST
Before writing properties, run the Coverage App. This immediately shows whether the FIFO's dead-code candidates are intentional or bugs. Any Unreachable transition in the FSM is a finding worth reviewing regardless of prior silicon history.

3. CORE PROPERTIES
- No push when full (overflow)
- No pop when empty (underflow)
- Occupancy counter matches actual entries in FIFO
- Data integrity: the symbolic scoreboard pattern — write sym_data to sym_addr, prove it comes back out in order
- Pointer wrap: write pointer wraps correctly at DEPTH, not at DEPTH-1 or DEPTH+1
- Full/empty flag correctness: assert full == (wr_ptr == rd_ptr + DEPTH) etc.

4. THE HARD ONE — data ordering
In most FIFOs this is the property that simulation never properly stress-tested. Use local variable capture pattern or symbolic scoreboard. Prove at depth = DEPTH+2 to cover the full wrap scenario.

5. APPROACH PREVIOUS DESIGNERS WITH EVIDENCE
Don't frame it as 'your FIFO is broken.' Frame it as 'here's what formal proves about it.' If you find a bug, the formal CEX is the conversation-starter, not the accusation.`},

{id:1404,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",
q:"Design an FPV environment for a parameterised round-robin arbiter with N requestors and configurable priority override.",
a:`Parameterised design = parameterised proof. This is a common senior question because it tests whether you can write scalable SVA.

PARAMETERISATION STRATEGY
Don't hardcode N. Write properties with generate loops so the same property file works for N=2, N=4, N=8, N=16. Prove for N=4 as the primary proof; use N=2 as a quick sanity configuration.

CORE PROPERTIES
genvar i, j;
generate
  // 1. Mutual exclusion — at most one grant
  ap_onehot: assert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)
    $onehot0(grant));

  // 2. Grant only when requested
  for (i=0; i<N; i++) begin : gen_grant
    ap_req_grant: assert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)
      grant[i] |-> req[i]);

    // 3. Bounded latency — every request eventually served (bounded)
    // Ghost variable: age counter per requestor
    ap_latency: assert property (@(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)
      req_age[i] >= MAX_WAIT |-> grant[i]);
  end

  // 4. Round-robin fairness — if all N requestors active, each gets one grant
  // in every N-cycle window. Harder to express in SVA — often done as cover
  cp_all_served: cover property (@(posedge clk)
    grant[0] ##[1:N] grant[1] ##[1:N] grant[2] ##[1:N] grant[3]);
endgenerate

PRIORITY OVERRIDE
Model override as a case split: run one proof with override inactive (prove fairness), one with override active (prove that the priority requestor always beats round-robin). Use set_case_analysis on override_en.

GHOST VARIABLES
req_age[i] counters in bind file — one per requestor, increments while req[i] is high and grant[i] is low.

CONVERGENCE
With N=4 and ghost latency counters, this should converge with Ht engine. N=8 may need counter abstraction on the age counters.`},

{id:1405,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",
q:"How would you formally verify a reset domain crossing (RDC) block — a module whose registers are reset by different reset signals?",
a:`RDC is structurally similar to CDC but for reset signals. Less tool support, so more manual work.

1. IDENTIFY THE RESETS
First step is always: list every reset signal in the block, which registers they control, and whether they're synchronous or asynchronous. Superlint's reset-completeness check gives you the register-to-reset mapping directly — run it first.

2. STRUCTURAL VERIFICATION
Check reset coverage: every flip-flop reachable by at least one reset path. Any FF with no reset path is a Superlint finding. Check also: if reset_A deasserts while reset_B is still asserted, is the design in a defined state? This is the core RDC safety question.

3. FPV PROPERTIES
For each pair of reset domains (reset_A, reset_B):

// When reset_A deasserts but reset_B is still active:
// outputs driven by reset_B domain must be in known reset state
ap_partial_reset_safe: assert property (
  @(posedge clk) disable iff (!reset_B)
  $rose(reset_A) |=> domain_B_output == RESET_VALUE);

// Data transferred from domain_A to domain_B must not be sampled
// during domain_B's reset — capture ordering
ap_no_capture_during_reset: assert property (
  @(posedge clk)
  !reset_B |-> !latch_enable_B);

4. RESET SEQUENCING
If your design requires reset_A to always deassert before reset_B: model this as an assume, then prove the design is safe. Then separately prove the assume is architecturally guaranteed (or document that the system integration must ensure it).

5. COMMON BUG
A register in domain_A is read by logic in domain_B. If domain_B resets while domain_A is still live, the domain_B consumer reads a stale value after its reset. FPV catches this because it can independently control reset_A and reset_B — simulation almost never does this.`},

{id:1406,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",
q:"You need to verify a multi-ported register file (4 read ports, 2 write ports, 32 registers × 32-bit). How do you approach this with FPV?",
a:`A 32×32 register file has 1024 state bits — on the edge of tractability. The approach is almost entirely abstraction-driven.

SYMBOLIC VARIABLE APPROACH (mandatory)
Never model the full register file in FPV. Use the symbolic address trick:

// One symbolic register index and symbolic data value
logic [4:0] sym_reg;   // free variable: 0–31
logic [31:0] sym_data; // free variable

// Track: was sym_data written to sym_reg?
logic written;
always_ff @(posedge clk or negedge rst_n)
  if (!rst_n) written <= 0;
  else if (wr_en_A && wr_addr_A==sym_reg && wr_data_A==sym_data) written <= 1;
  else if (wr_en_B && wr_addr_B==sym_reg && wr_data_B==sym_data) written <= 1;

// Assert: any read of sym_reg after write returns sym_data
generate for (genvar p=0; p<4; p++) begin : gen_rp
  ap_integrity: assert property (
    @(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)
    written && rd_addr[p]==sym_reg |-> rd_data[p]==sym_data);
end endgenerate

WRITE CONFLICT PROPERTIES
Two write ports targeting same address simultaneously — define the priority and prove it:
ap_write_conflict: assert property (
  @(posedge clk) wr_en_A && wr_en_B && wr_addr_A==wr_addr_B
  |=> rd_data[0] == wr_data_A);  // port A wins by spec

RESET
All registers reset to 0 — prove with symbolic approach: sym_reg can be any register, after reset, reading it returns 0.

CONVERGENCE
With symbolic abstraction: state space is ~5+32 bits (sym_reg + written flag + sym_data doesn't contribute to state). This converges cleanly. Without abstraction: 1024 bits → never converges.`},

{id:1407,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",
q:"A designer hands you an FSM with 24 states and tells you 'some of these states might be dead.' How do you handle this with FPV?",
a:`This is exactly the Coverage App's highest-value use case.

STEP 1 — COVERAGE APP, NOT MANUAL INSPECTION
Don't manually trace the state transition diagram. Run the Coverage App immediately:
check_coverage -type fsm

This gives you, for every state and every transition:
- Covered: formally reachable from reset under some input
- Unreachable: formally proven impossible — dead state
- Undetermined: couldn't resolve within proof depth

STEP 2 — INTERPRET THE UNREACHABLE STATES
For each Unreachable state, exactly one of three things is true:

1. Intentional dead state: the designer encoded 24 states but only 20 are used. The extra 4 are safe padding. Waive with justification.
2. RTL bug: a state was designed to be reachable (it's in the spec) but a guard condition or transition trigger has a logic error. The formal tool just found a real bug.
3. Over-constrained environment: your assume set is too tight, cutting off the input that would drive the FSM into that state. Loosen the assume and re-run.

STEP 3 — ILLEGAL STATE PROPERTIES
After dead-state analysis, write properties for the states that should never be reached from reset:
ap_no_illegal_state: assert property (
  @(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)
  state inside {LEGAL_STATE_LIST});

STEP 4 — TRANSITION COVERAGE
Run FSM transition coverage. An unreachable transition is often more interesting than an unreachable state — it means a valid state exists but a particular arc from it can never fire. Often indicates a missing condition in the RTL.

DELIVERABLE
Send the designer the formal Coverage App report with each Unreachable state annotated: intentional (waived) / bug (needs fix) / investigate. This is far more useful than 'I think states S12 and S17 look suspicious.'`},

{id:1408,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",
q:"How would you formally verify a scoreboard / out-of-order completion tracker that accepts requests and returns completions potentially out of order?",
a:`Out-of-order completion is one of the harder FPV problems because you need to track which response belongs to which request across an unbounded number of in-flight transactions.

THE CORE CHALLENGE
You cannot track all in-flight transactions simultaneously in FPV — the state space is proportional to the number of outstanding transactions × tag width. The symbolic variable trick solves this.

SYMBOLIC TRACKER APPROACH
// Symbolic tag — proves for all possible tags simultaneously
logic [TAG_W-1:0] sym_tag;
logic [DATA_W-1:0] sym_data;
logic issued, completed;

always_ff @(posedge clk or negedge rst_n) begin
  if (!rst_n) begin issued <= 0; completed <= 0; end
  else begin
    if (req_valid && req_tag==sym_tag && req_data==sym_data)
      issued <= 1;
    if (resp_valid && resp_tag==sym_tag && issued)
      completed <= 1;
  end
end

// Every request with sym_tag eventually gets a completion
ap_completion: assert property (
  @(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)
  issued && !completed |-> ##[1:MAX_OUTSTANDING] completed);

// Completion carries correct data
ap_data_integrity: assert property (
  @(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)
  resp_valid && resp_tag==sym_tag && issued
  |-> resp_data == sym_data);

// No duplicate completion for same tag
ap_no_dup: assert property (
  @(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)
  completed |-> !resp_valid || resp_tag != sym_tag);

ENVIRONMENT CONSTRAINTS
- Tag uniqueness: assume no two simultaneous outstanding requests share the same tag
- Bounded outstanding: assume at most MAX_OUTSTANDING requests in flight
- Response validity: assume resp_tag is always a tag of a previously-issued request

GHOST VARIABLE
The issued/completed state machine lives in a bind file.`},

{id:1409,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",
q:"Your manager asks why the FPV team's proofs keep being vacuous. What systematic process do you put in place to prevent this?",
a:`Vacuous proofs are a process failure, not just a technical one. Here's the systematic fix:

THE ROOT CAUSES (in order of frequency)
1. Antecedents that never fire — over-constrained environment blocks the triggering condition
2. Assumes that contradict the asserts — you've assumed the conclusion
3. Properties copy-pasted from a previous project without re-validating for the new design

THE PROCESS

Step 1 — Mandatory companion covers
For every assert property (A |-> B), write a paired:
cover property (@(posedge clk) A);
This is a gate requirement, not optional. No assert ships without its companion cover. If the cover is Uncovered, the assert is vacuous — stop, fix before continuing.

Step 2 — Run check_vacuity on every assert, every run
Add to your standard TCL script:
check_vacuity -all
Any property flagged is a blocker — must be resolved before results are reported.

Step 3 — check_assumptions every run
check_assumptions
If this reports contradictions, your entire proof run is meaningless. Fix assumes first.

Step 4 — Code review for assumes
Every assume property is reviewed by a second engineer before being committed. The review question: 'Does this assume reflect a real architectural constraint? Where in the spec is it documented?'

Step 5 — Mutation testing gates sign-off
No sign-off without a mutation score. If your mutation score is < 85%, properties aren't doing real work — either vacuous or too weak. The mutation score catches what check_vacuity misses (consequent vacuity).

Step 6 — RTL designer pairing session
The RTL designer walks the FV engineer through the design intent. This session catches assumes that are architecturally wrong — constraints that would never hold in the real system.

REPORTING
Track and report companion cover status alongside assert status in your weekly FV metrics. 'N asserts proven, M companion covers uncovered' tells management exactly where the risk is.`},

{id:1410,diff:"Interview",cat:"Interview Scenarios",
q:"How would you set up FPV for a clock gating cell controller that manages power domains?",
a:`Clock gating and power-aware FPV sits at the intersection of FPV and low-power — requires specific methodology.

TOOL SETUP
Use the JasperGold LP (Low Power) App or VC Formal FLP App rather than vanilla FPV. These apps understand UPF/CPF power intent and can model isolation cells, retention registers, and power switches formally.

If you're doing basic clock gate controller verification without UPF:

CLOCK GATING VERIFICATION WITHOUT UPF
The clock gate controller has inputs: enable, test_mode, clk_in. Output: clk_out (gated clock).

Core properties:
// Clock gate must not produce a glitch — output only changes on falling edge of clk_in
ap_no_glitch: assert property (
  @(negedge clk_in) disable iff (test_mode)
  clk_out == (clk_in && latch_q));

// Enable captured correctly into latch (level-sensitive, not edge)
ap_enable_latch: assert property (
  @(posedge clk_in) !latch_q |-> !enable || clk_in);

// DFT override: test_mode bypasses gate entirely
ap_dft_bypass: assert property (
  @(posedge clk_in) test_mode |-> clk_out == clk_in);

// No spurious enable deassert mid-clock
ap_stable_during_high: assert property (
  @(posedge clk_in) clk_out |=> $stable(latch_q));

POWER DOMAIN PROPERTIES
If verifying isolation cells:
// Outputs of powered-down domain must be held at isolation value
ap_isolation: assert property (
  @(posedge clk) disable iff (!rst_n)
  !domain_powered |-> iso_output == ISO_VALUE);

// Retention register retains value across power cycle
ap_retention: assert property (
  @(posedge clk)
  power_off ##[1:$] $rose(power_on) |=> reg_out == $past(reg_in, 1));

ENVIRONMENT
set_case_analysis 1 {dut.dft_mode} for DFT bypass runs.
set_case_analysis 0 {dut.dft_mode} for functional runs.
Never verify both modes simultaneously — case-split to keep COI manageable.`}

);
